# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-f-young
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] While the core of academic freedom covers scholars acting in an academic capacity (as teachers or researchers expressing strictly scholarly viewpoints), an expansive interpretation extends these occupational safeguards to scholars' speech on matters outside their professional expertise.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic tenure protects academic freedom by ensuring that teachers can be fired only for causes such as gross professional incompetence or behavior that evokes condemnation from the academic community itself.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The academic community pressuring scholars can reduce academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Historically, academic freedom emerged tentatively, as academics in medieval and early modern Europe could face repression for acting in ways considered objectionable by religious authorities or by governments.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Scholars tend to link the institutionalization of academic freedom to the rise of the modern research university and the Humboldtian model of higher education from the 19th century.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] By one estimate, academic freedom has substantially increased worldwide since the 1960s.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is more likely in liberal democratic states, while it is more heavily constrained in authoritarian states, illiberal states, and states embroiled in military conflict.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Since 2013, while some countries have seen improvements to academic freedom, the overall trend is towards reductions in freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] A minimal definition of academic freedom is that a teacher has a right to instruct, and a student has a right to learn in an academic setting unhampered by interference.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Other definitions include the right of teachers to engage in social and political criticism.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] A broader definition of academic freedom incorporates individual, extramural and institutional components.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Under this broader definition, an academic has freedom of expression without government interference, but this freedom is circumscribed by academic expertise and position.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom of speech is therefore narrower than a general freedom of speech.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] For example, a non-academic has the freedom of speech to criticize the efficacy of vaccines, but only has *academic freedom* to do so if they possess the prerequisite academic qualifications to do so.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Unlike public speech, academic speech is also subject to quality controls by academic peers, for example through peer review.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Norwegian education sees it as a guarantee that research and teaching is "intellectually and morally independent of all political and economic interests", leading to openness, free enquiry and debate.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The laissez-faire approach of unaccountable academic freedom is contrasted with democratic accountability of academia.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Historically, academic freedom emerged tentatively.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 1155, the Holy Roman Emperor Frederick I Barbarossa issued the document *Authentica habita* which laid out rights and privileges of students and scholars, which included immunity from civil jurisdiction and freedom of movement for the purposes of studying and teaching.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Similarly, civil disturbances, such as the St Scholastica Day riot of 1355 at the University of Oxford often led to great autonomy for universities.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] And even those scholars who committed theological heresy, such as John Wyclif and Jan Hus, has support due to their roles as faculty at a university.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The Humboldtian model of higher education from the 19th century enshrined the basic ideas of academic freedom and diffused them to other countries.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Wilhelm von Humboldt was a philosopher and linguist who was given the authority to create a new university in Berlin in the early 19th century.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In founding the Humboldt University of Berlin he created a university that adhered to two principles of academic freedom: freedom of scientific inquiry and the unity between research and teaching.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] According to Humboldt, the fundamental proposition underlying the principles of academic freedom was to uphold the view that science is not something that has already been found but as knowledge that will never be fully discovered and, yet, needs to be searched for unceasingly.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The university he founded later became a model and inspiration for modern colleges in Germany and universities in the West.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] During this period there was also a sense that universities must be insulated from the pressures of donors, boards of trustees and state governments.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] One notable instance was the case of the resignation of Brown University president Elisha Andrews, who advocated silver coinage to reduce the impact on Americans and farmers who owed larger and larger loans due to deflation.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The board of Brown University, many of whom were creditors and landowners and benefited from deflation, told Andrews to cease his public advocacy.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The dean of Yale Law School, Francis Wayland, argued that Andrews' free expression threatened donations to Brown, and that money was the life blood of universities.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 1897, Andrews was forced to offer his resignation, but there was a backlash by faculty and students who advocated that he should be protected under the principles of free speech.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The board reversed its decision and refused Andrews' resignation.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The concept of academic freedom was also formulated in response to the encroachments of the totalitarian state on science and academia in general for the furtherance of its own goals.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] For instance, in the Soviet Union, scientific research was brought under strict political control in the 1930s.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] A number of research areas were declared "bourgeois pseudoscience" and forbidden, notably genetics (see "Lysenkoism") and sociology.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Marxist scientist John Desmond Bernal characterized this as part of the interdependence between "applied science" and "pure science".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Michael Polanyi argued that a structure of liberty is essential for the advancement of science.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 1936, as a consequence of an invitation to give lectures for the Ministry of Heavy Industry in the USSR, Polanyi met Bukharin, who told him that in socialist societies all scientific research is directed to accord with the needs of the latest five-year plan.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Demands in Britain for centrally planned scientific research led Polanyi, together with John Baker, to found the Society for Freedom in Science.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The society promoted a liberal conception of science as free enquiry against the instrumental view that science should exist primarily to serve the needs of society.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In a series of articles, re-published in *The Contempt of Freedom* (1940) and *The Logic of Liberty* (1951), Polanyi claimed that co-operation among scientists is analogous to the way in which agents co-ordinate themselves within a free market.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Just as consumers in a free market determine the value of products, science is a spontaneous order that arises as a consequence of open debate among specialists.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Proponents of academic freedom believe that the freedom of inquiry by students and faculty members is essential to the mission of the academy.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] They argue that academic communities are repeatedly targeted for repression due to their ability to shape and control the flow of information.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] When scholars attempt to teach or communicate ideas or facts that are inconvenient to external political groups or to authorities, they may find themselves targeted for public vilification, job loss, imprisonment, or even death.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] For example, in North Africa, a professor of public health discovered that his country's infant mortality rate was higher than government figures indicated.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The fate of biology in the Soviet Union is cited by Jasper Becker as a reason why society has an interest in protecting academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Lysenko called this "Michurinism", but it is more commonly known today as Lysenkoism, and named after him.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Lysenko's ideas appealed to the Soviet leadership, in part because of their value as propaganda, and he was ultimately made director of the Soviet Academy of Agricultural Sciences.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Subsequently, Lysenko directed a purge of scientists who professed "harmful ideas", resulting in the expulsion, imprisonment, or death of hundreds of Soviet scientists.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Lysenko's ideas were then implemented on collectivized farms in the Soviet Union and China.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Famines that resulted partly from Lysenko's influence are believed to have killed 30 million people in China alone during the Great Leap Forward.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Sociologist Ruth Pearce argued that the concept of academic freedom exists to protect scholarship from censure by state or religious authorities or others, and not to defend intolerance.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom can be reduced through scholars pressuring other scholars and resulting self-censorship or political bias.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] A large-scale empirical study, covering more than 157 countries over the 1900-2015 period, links academic freedom to the quality and quantity of patents filed in a given country.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] David Audretsch and colleagues estimate that academic freedom has declined over the last decade for the first time over their century-long observation period, resulting in at least 4% fewer patents filed.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The study claims to be the first to link academic freedom to economic growth through an innovation channel.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom has also been identified as a leading indicator for whether a government will become more or less democratic.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2020, the V-Dem Institute partnered with Scholars at Risk to create the first index of Academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The index provides retroactive ratings for countries going back to 1900 that are also updated yearly.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] As of 2025, academic freedom overall around the world has been in retreat since 2013.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Causes cited have included authoritarianism as well as political polarization and populism.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The concept of academic freedom as a right of faculty members is an established part of most legal systems.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] While in the United States the constitutional protection of academic freedom derives from the guarantee of free speech under the First Amendment, the constitutions of other countries (particularly in civil law systems) typically grant a separate right to free learning, teaching, and research.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Concerns have been expressed by Freedom House and others about protections for freedom of speech and academic freedom at Australia's universities.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2018, the Australian Government asked former Chief Justice Robert French to conduct an independent review of freedom of speech and academic freedom in Australian higher education.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] While French disagreed that there was a "freedom of speech crisis" on campuses, he nonetheless noted the risks to freedom posed by the various and vaguely-worded protections then in place.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Concerns include the influence of the People's Republic of China on university administrations; 'deplatforming' of controversial speakers and viewpoints; and demands that academics refrain from contesting one another's conclusions.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] During the late 1950s and early 1960s, students and faculty began advocating for the democratization of university life in Chile.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] However, after the 1973 coup, academic freedom under the Pinochet military dictatorship was repressed.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Nevertheless, during the 1980s, students and faculty, with support from members of the public, collaborated to protect academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Since the transition to democracy after the end of the Pinochet regime in 1990, academic freedom in higher education in Chile has been strong.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2025, Chile ranked in the top ten percent of countries on the Academic Freedom Index (AFI).
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is severely limited in China.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academics have noted an incentive not to express 'incorrect' opinions about issues sensitive to the Government of China and the ruling Chinese Communist Party (CCP).
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] These efforts have been effective in causing academics to self-censor and shift academic discourse.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] During the general secretaryship of Xi Jinping, universities in the country have increasingly been put under the direct management of a CCP committee secretary and have intensified ideological controls.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In December 2020, the Associated Press reported that China was controlling scientific research into the origins of COVID-19 under direct orders from CCP general secretary Xi Jinping.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] According to the report, an order by China's State Council required all research to be approved by a task force under their management, saying scientific publication should be orchestrated like "a game of chess", warning that those who publish without permission will be held accountable.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] According to National Public Radio, from 2013 to 2017, at least 109 universities in China issued their first charters affirming the CCP leadership.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2020, Shanghai's Fudan University removed freedom of thought from its charter following the December 2019 revision of the school charter to emphasize loyalty to the CCP.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Hong Kong academia expressed concerns about the impact of the 2020 Hong Kong National Security Law on academic freedom in Hong Kong.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] As of 2025, it ranked in the bottom 20% worldwide for academic freedom according to the Academic Freedom Index.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In an August 2021 study, Jue Jiang from the University of London argued that academic freedom in China is impaired by the CCP's system of student informants, who are recruited and encouraged to watch and inform on their professors on university campuses.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Danish law guarantees both institutional and individual academic freedom at universities, yet the country ranked 24th of 28 EU states in 2017 and 32nd of 179 countries in a 2024 study.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Researchers and the academic union DM reported in 2024 that political pressure, insecure employment, competition for external funding and limited public awareness are weakening independence and discouraging basic research.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2021, a political campaign against alleged “pseudo-research and activism” led to parliamentary resolution V137, with some politicians demanding interventions, lists of “dangerous” programmes and the closure of certain research fields.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Over 3,000 academics signed a petition arguing the resolution threatened academic freedom and could increase self-censorship and harassment, including on social media.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Earlier and ongoing controversies include the 1986 government-ordered closure of a sociology programme at Copenhagen University and recent proposals from Danish People's Party and Liberal Alliance to shut down Roskilde University for ideological reasons, including for being 'woke'.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Central European University was forced to leave Hungary after its academic freedom deteriorated under Victor Orban.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2020, students protested the overhauling by the government of the University of Theater and Film Arts.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] As of 2025, India ranks in the bottom 10-20% of countries globally.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Protections for academic freedom for research, teaching and other activity "to question and test received wisdom, to put forward new ideas and to state controversial or unpopular opinions" without being disadvantaged, are provided in Section 14 of the 1997 Universities Act.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom in Israel is taken from "the Law of the Council for Higher Education".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Paragraph 15 in which it states that "a recognized institution is free to all its academic and administrative matters, within the framework of its budget, as it sees fit.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] It seems that the paragraph is worded in a clear and comprehensible way even for laymen.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The body that is supposed to guard academic freedom, as well as maintain an adequate academic level in the higher education institutions, is the Council for Higher Education – hereinafter "The Council".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This council consists of academics who serve as professors at universities, and public figures, with the Minister of Education as the head of the council.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] At the disposal of "The Council" is an executive body called the "Committee for Planning and Budgeting", which mainly deals with the matter of universities budgeting and establishing relevant procedures and guidelines for budget and salary matters.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Another body that is supposed to guard academic freedom is the "Committee of the Heads of the Universities", which is a voluntary body, but has an influence on the work of the Legislature and "The Council ".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Through their employee committees, and through the personal activity of each of them, these bodies can try and influence the preservation of academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In general, it can be said that the essential academic freedom, the one aimed at the freedom of teaching and research, was preserved, and the government neither interfered nor tried to interfere in these contents.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Its way of influencing this matter is by providing incentives for teaching in this or that way, or for research in certain fields, and this is through grants.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The fact that the government finances a significant percentage of the current budget of the universities (around 70% or more), also allows the government to decide what will be the tuition fee for a student at the budgeted universities in Israel.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] But, In 2021, an academic committee of the prestigious Israel Prize decided to award the Israel Prize in the field of mathematics and computer science to Professor Oded Goldreich from the Weizmann Institute of Science.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The award committee appealed to the Supreme Court for a violation of its academic freedom, and the court overturned the decision, and ordered the Minister of Education to award Goldreich the award.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Godreich received the award a year later.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In recent years, a fierce debate has erupted on the issue of academic freedom, following extreme political statements by a number of university faculty members.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The vast majority of the controversial statements were those that called for an academic boycott of Israel, or support for organizations that support an economic and academic boycott of Israel.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] All the more, is it permissible for the professor to express a political position during his teaching, and even to invite representatives of political bodies to lecture in his classes, and without maintaining a balance between those invited.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Referring to that background, the Minister of Education at the time Naftali Bennett (in 2017) asked Prof.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Asa Kasher to compile an academic Code of Ethics for universities, a code that was approved by "The Council" in March 2018.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] All the research universities (7 universities), with the exception of Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, which already had for an academic code of ethics that also included the issue of freedom of expression, refused to adopt this code on the grounds of infringing academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] All research universities in Israel have a Chief internal auditor, relatively independent.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In the Chapter II Constitution of Mauritius, academics have the right to: the protection of freedom of conscience, protection of freedom of expression, protection of freedom of assembly and association, protection of freedom to establish schools and the protection from discrimination.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The institutional bureaucracy and the dependence on the state for funds has restricted the freedom of academics to criticize government policy.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom became a public issue in May 2009 when the university spoke out against the vice chancellor Professor I.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Fagoonee, who had forwarded a circular sent by the Ministry of Education to academics.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This circular targeted public officers and required them to consult their superiors before speaking to the press.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The pushback resulted in the vice chancellor stepping down, with the author speculating the government used the vice chancellor as the scapegoat for its unpopular proposal to try to curtail academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In the Netherlands the academic freedom is limited relative to other Western European countries.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In November 1985 the Dutch Ministry of Education published a policy paper titled *Higher Education: Autonomy and Quality*.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This paper had a proposal that steered away from traditional education and informed that the future of higher education sector should not be regulated by the central government.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 1992 the Law of Higher Education and Research (Wet op het hoger onderwijs en wetenschappelijk onderzoek, article 1.6) was published and became effective in 1993.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] However, this law governs only certain institutions.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is protected by the 1987 Philippine Constitution, which states in Article XIV, Section 5 (2), "Academic freedom shall be enjoyed in all institutions of higher learning".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Republic Act 8292 (Higher Education Modernization Act of 1997) states that "all institutions of higher learning, public or private, shall enjoy academic freedom and institutional autonomy".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Implementing rules for this law state that "all SUCs shall enjoy academic freedom and institutional autonomy".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is also enshrined in Republic Act 9500 (The University of the Philippines Charter of 2008), which states, "the national university has the right and responsibility to exercise academic freedom".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Threats to academic freedom include attempts to establish a military presence in campuses or corporations dictating that a school teach only "marketable courses".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Other threats may come in the form of state-sponsored historical distortion and the red-tagging, surveillance, and harassment of students and faculty.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In Freedom House's 2025 Academic Freedom Index, the Philippines scored 0.624 (out of 1, 1 is best), the country's lowest score in nearly 40 years.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] According to the FAU Academic Freedom Index, in 2025 South Africa scored a 0.83 on a scale of 0 to 1, which has been pretty constant between 2015 to 2025.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Section 16(1) of the Constitution of the Republic of South Africa, established in 1996, guarantees everyone the right to freedom of expression, including “academic freedom and freedom of scientific research".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Under apartheid, universities were racially segregated, a legacy that influences the lives of students and academics in South Africa today.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The Population Registration Act of 1950 classified South Africans by race, using categories of White, Indian, Coloured, and Black.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Based on this legislation, the Extension of University Education Act 45 dictated that students of nonwhite descent were not permitted to register at traditionally white universities unless given expression permission by the minister.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] As a result, several non-white universities were established, including the University of Durban-Westville for Indians, and the University of the Western Cape at Belleville, open to the Coloured community.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Fort Hare University, University of Zululand, and the University of the North at Turfloop were established or reformed as institutions for specific ethnic groups.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The higher education system remained starkly segregated until 1988, when the National Party government, led by F.W. de Klerk, put forth a set of policies repealing various systematic segregationist laws.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] As of 2007, there have been scandals over the restricted academic freedom at a number of universities in South Africa.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The University of KwaZulu-Natal received fame over its restricted academic freedom and the scandal that occurred in 2007.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Fazel Khan was fired in April 2007 for "bringing the university into disrepute" after releasing information to the news media about being airbrushed from a photograph in a campus publication because of his participation in a staff strike.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The South African Council on Higher Education released a report stating that the state is influencing academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Public universities are more susceptible to political pressure because they receive funds from the public.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Among postdoctoral fellows, there exist sentiments of being taken advantage of, based on the personal testimonies of postdoctoral fellows at the University of Johannesburg.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] While these conversations occur in many postdoctoral settings, much of the conversation arises from South Africa, where fellows report that the unstable nature of postdoctoral contracts is lends itself to insufficient compensation disproportionate to the demand for fellows.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Multiple accounts and reports from postdoctoral fellows have shown two conflicting ideas: one believing the postdoc system to be a reliable pathway for a future scholarly career and one perceiving the system as unreliable and exploitive.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Institutional capture and patronage networks, informal institutions intertwined with South Africa's academic landscape, Jonas Magedi argues, compromises the integrity of higher education.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Specifically, pressure from external sources may suppress dissent and inhibit further growth, especially in the area of humanities.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2016, Erdogan was given the power to appoint professors by decree.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This, along with firings, harassment and imprisonment of academics helped to drop Turkey to one of the countries with the lowest academic freedom in the world by 2021, leading to protests at institutions like Boğaziçi University.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The Robbins Report on Higher Education, commissioned by the British government and published in 1963, devoted a full chapter, Chapter XVI, to Academic freedom and its scope.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This gives a detailed discussion of the importance attached both to freedom of individual academics and of the institution itself.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In a world, both then and now, where illiberal governments are all too ready to attack freedom of expression, the Robbins committee saw the (then) statutory protection given to academic freedom as giving some protection for society as a whole from any temptation to mount such attacks.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] When Margaret Thatcher's government sought to remove many of the statutory protections of academic freedom which Robbins had regarded as so important, she was partly frustrated by a hostile amendment to her bill in the House of Lords.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] These principles of academic freedom are thus articulated in the statutes of most UK universities.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Professor Kathleen Stock formerly of University of Sussex resigned from her role due to controversy from students and the media regarding her transphobic views.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In response to such concerns, the Equality and Human Rights Commission has issued guidance.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The Guidance provides detailed procedures for universities to consider in determining whether or not specific events can go ahead.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] It also provides ways to reduce any potential barriers for freedom of speech in regards to specific events.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The guidance also makes clear the statutory requirement of universities to ensure they protect freedom of speech on campus however as well as compliance with the Prevent Strategy and the Equality Act 2010.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom started in America after the Civil War disrupted the previously stagnating systems of higher education.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The educational system that Germany had was analyzed by universities to progress fields of research.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Johns Hopkins University was the first to use this education system.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Prior to the turn of the twentieth century, a professor by the name of Edward Ross published the free silver movement supporting document known as *Honest Dollars.* The document placed the professor in political disagreement with the founders of Stanford University.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The Stanford family made their money from the railroad industry that the professor had publicly ridiculed.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 1900, the professor expressed politically charged statements that called for the expulsion of Japanese immigrants from the country which would lead to his termination from the university.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This decision was followed by seven other professors resigning from the university and elevated the matter to national scrutiny.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This event would set in motion the creation of the AAUP to provide monetary and legal security, filling the gaps in many of their contracts.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The principle also refers to the ability of teachers, students, and educational institutions to pursue knowledge without unreasonable political or government interference.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The Principles have only the character of private pronouncements, not that of binding law.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In short the statement argues that professors have the privilege to search for truth and knowledge and the right to impart those truths and knowledge to others, including students, the academy, and the general public, unfettered by political or ideological pressure.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Since being drafted, this definition has undergone two revisions in 1970 and 1999 respectively.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The 1970 revision declares that the protections of academic freedom "apply not only to the full-time probationary and the tenured teacher, but also to all others, such as part-time faculty and teaching assistants, who exercise teaching responsibilities".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The 1999 revision places emphasis on the idea that post-tenure review should be conducted in a manner that respects academic freedom and due process.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Supreme Court began to take up the matter starting with the case of *Sweezy v.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Board of Regents* (1967), the Supreme Court made connections between the First Amendment and academic freedom as an especially important protection on the grounds that it was crucial to everyone.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Such First Amendment protections only applied to public institutions, and academic freedom contains protections outside of the First Amendment as the Court never outright declared that it contained academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Some accreditors work with American colleges and universities, including private and religious institutions, to support academic freedom in various forms, although this varies by accreditor.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Additionally, the AAUP, which is not an accrediting body, works with these same institutions.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The AAUP does not always agree with the accrediting bodies on the standards of protection of academic freedom and tenure.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The AAUP censures those colleges and universities which it has found, after its own investigations, to violate these principles.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] By 2022, 88 percent of four-year colleges and universities will limit student free speech, reversing a 15-year trend, according to the College Speech Codes annual report.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression (FIRE) reported that 426 out of 486 institutions have at least one policy restricting student speech.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] A prominent feature of the English university concept is the freedom to appoint faculty, set standards and admit students.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This ideal may be better described as institutional autonomy and is distinct from whatever freedom is granted to students and faculty by the institution.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In a 2008 case, a federal court in Virginia ruled that professors have no academic freedom; *all* academic freedom resides with the university or college.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Virginia State University*, a district court judge held "that no constitutional right to academic freedom exists that would prohibit senior (university) officials from changing a grade given by (a professor) to one of his students." The court relied on mandatory precedent of the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] New Hampshire* and a case from the fourth circuit court of appeals.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The *Stronach* court also relied on persuasive cases from several circuits of the courts of appeals, including the first, third, and seventh circuits.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] That court distinguished the situation when a university attempts to coerce a professor into changing a grade, which is clearly in violation of the First Amendment, from when university officials may, in their discretionary authority, change the grade upon appeal by a student.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The *Stronach* case has gotten significant attention in the academic community as an important precedent.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom and free speech rights are not coextensive, although this widely accepted view has been challenged by an "institutionalist" perspective on the First Amendment.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom involves more than speech rights; for example, it includes the right to determine what is taught in the classroom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The AAUP gives teachers a set of guidelines to follow when their ideas are considered threatening to religious, political, or social agendas.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In practice, academic freedom is protected by institutional rules and regulations, letters of appointment, faculty handbooks, collective bargaining agreements, and academic custom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In the U.S., the freedom of speech is guaranteed by the First Amendment, which states that "Congress shall make no law... abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press...." By extension, the First Amendment applies to all governmental institutions, including public universities.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Supreme Court has historically held that academic freedom is a First Amendment right at *public* institutions.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] However, the United States' First Amendment has generally been held to **not** apply to *private* institutions, including religious institutions.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] These private institutions may honor freedom of speech and academic freedom at their discretion.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is also associated with a movement to introduce intelligent design as an alternative explanation to evolution in US public schools.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Critics of the movement claim intelligent design is religiously motivated pseudoscience and cannot be allowed into the curriculum of US public schools due to the First Amendment to the United States Constitution, often citing *Kitzmiller v.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Dover Area School District* as legal precedent.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] They also reject the allegations of discrimination against proponents of intelligent design, of which investigation showed no evidence.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] A number of "academic freedom bills" have been introduced in state legislatures in the United States between 2004 and 2008.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The bills were based largely upon language drafted by the Discovery Institute, the hub of the Intelligent Design movement, and derive from language originally drafted for the Santorum Amendment in the United States Senate.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, the common goal of these bills is to expose more students to articles and videos that undercut evolution, most of which are produced by advocates of intelligent design or biblical creationism.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The American Association of University Professors has reaffirmed its opposition to these bills, including any portrayal of creationism as a scientifically credible alternative and any misrepresentation of evolution as scientifically controversial.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] As of 2013, only the Louisiana bill has been successfully passed into law.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2014, a debate was held by the Academic Leadership Fellows Program (ALFP), addressing the potential need to either further revise the text, overhaul it completely, or leave it as is.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The counterargument to revision/overhaul asserts that the AAUP's statement has aged well, and that overhauling the standard that has existed for decades would only stir up further confusion.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Instead, it is necessary to "clearly articulate the statements' intended meaning through education, discussion, and by not supporting inappropriate behavior in the name of academic freedom".
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] This debate took place in front of a live audience, who after hearing both arguments agreed overwhelmingly with keeping the statement as-is.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In the 20th century and particularly the 1950s during McCarthyism, there was much public date in print on Communism's role in academic freedom, e.g., Sidney Hook's *Heresy, Yes–Conspiracy, No* and Whittaker Chambers' "Is Academic Freedom in Danger?" among many other books and articles.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] While some controversies of academic freedom are reflected in proposed laws that would affect large numbers of students through entire regions, many cases involve individual academics that express unpopular opinions or share politically unfavorable information.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] These individual cases may receive widespread attention and periodically test the limits of, and support for, academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Several of these specific cases are also the foundations for later legislation.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 1929, Experimental Psychology professor Max Friedrich Meyer and sociology assistant professor Harmon O.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] The university was subsequently censured by the American Association of University Professors in an early case regarding academic freedom due a tenured professor.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2006, Lawrence Summers, while president of Harvard University, led a discussion that was intended to identify the reasons why fewer women chose to study science and mathematics at advanced levels.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] He suggested that the possibility of intrinsic gender differences in terms of talent for science and mathematics should be explored.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] He became the target of considerable public backlash.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] His critics were, in turn, accused of attempting to suppress academic freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Due to the adverse reception to his comments, he resigned after a five-year tenure.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Another significant factor of his resignation was several votes of no-confidence placed by the deans of schools, notably multiple professors in the Faculty of Arts and Sciences.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2009 Thio Li-ann withdrew from an appointment at New York University School of Law after controversy erupted about some anti-gay remarks she had made, prompting a discussion of academic freedom within the law school.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Subsequently, Li-ann was asked to step down from her position in the NYU Law School.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] In 2009 the University of California at Santa Barbara accused William I.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Robinson of antisemitism after he circulated an email to his class containing photographs and paragraphs of the Holocaust juxtaposed to those of the Gaza Strip.
[src:alfred-f-young/academic-freedom] Robinson was fired from the university, but later the accusations were dropped after a worldwide campaign against the management of the university.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] Alfred Fabian Young, known to family and friends as "Al," was born January 17, 1925, in New York City.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] He was the second son of Gerson Yungowitz, a Polish-born Jew who had grown up in London, and the former Fanny Denitzen, an East European émigré to America.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] The family surname was Americanized to Young after his father's arrival in America.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] His parents divorced when Al was a child and he was raised by his mother in suburban Jamaica, New York.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] Young attended public schools, graduating from Jamaica High School in Jamaica, Queens at the age of 16, academically ranked 4th in his class of 400 students.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] He subsequently attended Queens College, from which he graduated in 1946 with a Bachelor of Arts degree in Economics.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] Young went on to earn a Master's degree from Columbia University in 1947, from whence he moved to Northwestern University near Chicago, where he began work on a PhD.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] After three years of course work at Northwestern, Young took a series of teaching jobs at three eastern universities, while continuing to work on his dissertation in his spare time.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] He was ultimately awarded his PhD by Northwestern in 1958.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] His thesis title was "The Democratic-Republican movement in New York State, 1788-1797".
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] In 1952 Young married Marilyn Mills, with whom he ultimately raised three daughters.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] After working in a series of temporary positions, in 1964 Young was hired by Northern Illinois University to a tenure track position in the field of American history.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] He would continue to teach there for a quarter century before his retirement in 1989.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] His first book, *The Democratic Republicans of New York: The Origins, 1763-1797,* was published in 1967 and won accolades from the Institute of Early American History and Culture, which awarded it its Jamestown Prize.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] During the tumultuous era of the Vietnam War, Young emerged as an outspoken advocate of academic freedom and the defense of college professors with political views outside the mainstream from employment retaliation.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] He was the founder of the Committee on Academic Freedom in Illinois in 1968, an organization formed to halt the blacklisting of radical historian Staughton Lynd, and was active in the Committee on the Rights of Historians of the American Historical Association from its inception in 1971.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] After his retirement from teaching, Young took a position as a Senior Scholar in Residence at the Newberry Library in Chicago.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] He also published an important biography of a seldom-remembered colonial woman who assumed a male gender identity in order to fight in the Revolutionary War, *Masquerade: The Live and Times of Deborah Sampson, Continental Soldier* (2005).
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] In 2004, Young was a founding editor of the academic journal *Labor: Studies in Working-Class History of the Americas,* published today by Duke University Press.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] Al Young was stricken by his first heart attack in May 2012.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] His productive work as a working historian was thereby brought to an end.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] Young died November 6, 2012, in Durham, North Carolina, following a second heart attack — this time fatal.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] He was 87 years old at the time of his death.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] Young was remembered by his peers as a scholar of broad intellect with an exhaustive knowledge of his area of specialization.
[src:alfred-f-young/alfred-f-young] Characterizing him as a "New Left historian before there was a New Left," historian Michael D.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The **American Historical Association** (**AHA**) is the oldest professional association of historians in the United States and the largest such organization in the world with 11,000 members as of 2025.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Founded in 1884, AHA works to protect academic freedom, develop professional standards, and support scholarship and innovative teaching.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] It publishes *The American Historical Review* four times annually, which features scholarly history-related articles and book reviews.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] AHA is the major learned society for historians working in the United States, while the Organization of American Historians is a field society for historians who study and teach about the United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] AHA operates as an umbrella organization for the discipline of history, and works with other major historical organizations and acts as a public advocate for the field.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Within the profession, the association defines ethical behavior and best practices, particularly through its "Statement on Standards of Professional Conduct".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] AHA also develops standards for good practice in teaching and history textbooks.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The AHA publishes *The American Historical Review*, a major journal of history scholarship covering all historical topics since ancient history and *Perspectives on History*, the monthly news magazine of the profession.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] In 2006 the AHA started a blog focused on the latest happenings in the broad discipline of history and the professional practice of the craft that draws on the staff, research, and activities of the AHA.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The association's annual meeting each January brings together more than 5,000 historians from around the United States to discuss the latest research and discuss how to be better historians and teachers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Many affiliated historical societies hold their annual meetings simultaneously.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The association's web site offers extensive information on the current state of the profession, tips on history careers, and an extensive archive of historical materials (including the G.I.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Roundtable series), a series of pamphlets prepared for the War Department in World War II.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The AHA also administers two major fellowships, 24 book prizes, and a number of small research grants.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The association elects a president to serve a one-year term; the president for 2026 is Lonnie Bunch.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The early leaders of the association were mostly gentlemen with the leisure and means to write many of the great 19th-century works of history, such as George Bancroft, Justin Winsor, and James Ford Rhodes.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] However, as former AHA president James J.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Thavolia Glymph was elected president of the AHA for the term beginning in 2024.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The 140th president, she is the first Black woman to hold that post.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] From its founding, the association was largely managed by historians employed at colleges and universities, and served a critical role in defining their interests as a profession.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The association's first president, Andrew Dickson White, was president of Cornell University, and its first secretary, Herbert Baxter Adams, established one of the first history Ph.D. programs to follow the new German seminary method at Johns Hopkins University.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The clearest expression of this academic impulse in history came in the development of the *American Historical Review* in 1895.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Formed by historians at a number of the most important universities in the United States, it followed the model of European history journals.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Franklin Jameson, the *Review* published several long scholarly articles every issue, only after they had been vetted by scholars and approved by the editor.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Each issue also reviewed a number of history books for their conformity to the new professional norms and scholarly standards that were taught at leading graduate schools to Ph.D. candidates.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] From the AHR, Sheehan concludes, "a junior scholar learned what it meant to be a historian of a certain sort".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Meringolo (2004) compares academic and public history.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Unlike academic history, public history is typically a collaborative effort, does not necessarily rely on primary research, is more democratic in participation, and does not aspire to absolute "scientific" objectivity.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Historical museums, documentary editing, heritage movements and historical preservation are considered public history.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Though activities now associated with public history originated in the AHA, these activities separated out in the 1930s due to differences in methodology, focus, and purpose.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The foundations of public history were laid on the middle ground between academic history and the public audience by National Park Service administrators during the 1920s–30s.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The academicians insisted on a perspective that looked beyond particular localities to a larger national and international perspective, and that in practice it should be done along modern and scientific lines.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] To that end, the association actively promoted excellence in the areas of research, the association published a series of annual reports through the Smithsonian Institution and adopted *The American Historical Review* in 1898 to provide early outlets for this new brand of professional scholarship.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] In 1896, the association appointed a "Committee of Seven" to develop a national standard for college admission requirements in the field of history.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Before this time, individual colleges defined their own entrance requirements.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] After substantial surveys of prevailing teaching methods, emphases and curricula in secondary schools, the Committee published "The Study of History in Schools" in 1898.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Their report largely defined the way history would be taught at the high school level as a preparation for college, and wrestled with issues about how the field should relate to the other social studies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The Committee recommended four blocks of Western history, to be taught in chronological order—ancient, medieval and modern European, English, and American history and civil government—and advised that teachers "tell a story" and "bring out dramatic aspects" to make history come alive.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The association also played a decisive role in lobbying the federal government to preserve and protect its own documents and records.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] After extensive lobbying by AHA Secretary Waldo Leland and Jameson, Congress established the National Archives and Records Administration in 1934.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] As the interests of historians in colleges and universities gained prominence in the association, other areas and activities tended to fall by the wayside.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The Manuscripts and Public Archives Commissions were abandoned in the 1930s, while projects related to original research and the publication of scholarship gained ever-greater prominence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] The association historically avoided addressing contemporary politics and made no statements on the Vietnam War or South African apartheid.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] In 2007, the group Historians for Peace and Democracy presented a resolution against the Iraq War, which passed under president Barbara Weinstein.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] At the 2025 annual meeting, AHA members passed a resolution condemning alleged scholasticide in the Israel-Gaza War by a 428-to-88 vote.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-historical-association] Association elected council vetoed the resolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The **American Revolution** (1765–1789) was a political movement in the Thirteen Colonies of Great Britain.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The movement began as a rebellion and evolved into a revolution resulting in the sovereign United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] These changes were the outcome of the associated American Revolutionary War.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress, as the provisional government, established the Continental Army and appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief in 1775.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The following year, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution on July 2nd, then unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence on the Fourth of July.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Throughout most of the war, the outcome appeared uncertain.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] However, in 1781, a decisive victory by Washington and the Continental Army in the Siege of Yorktown led King George III and the Fox–North coalition in government to negotiate the cessation of colonial rule and the acknowledgment of American sovereignty, formalized in the Treaty of Paris in 1783.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Constitution took effect in 1789 and the Bill of Rights was ratified in 1791.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Discontent with colonial rule began shortly after the French and Indian War ended in 1763.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Even though the colonies had fought in and supported the war directly with troops, funds and material, the British Parliament imposed new taxes to ostensibly compensate for wartime costs, and transferred control of the colonies' western lands to British officials in Montreal.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Representatives from several colonies convened in New York City for the Stamp Act Congress in 1765; its "Declaration of Rights and Grievances" argued that this taxation without representation in Parliament and other policies violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, though the Stamp Act was repealed, tensions flared again following Parliament's passage of the Townshend Acts.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In an effort to quell the mounting rebellion, King George III deployed British troops to the colony of Massachusetts, where they killed antagonists in the 1770 Boston Massacre.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In December 1773, the local faction of the colonies-wide Sons of Liberty underground orchestrated the Boston Tea Party, during which they dumped chests of taxed tea owned by the British East India Company into Boston Harbor.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Parliament responded by enacting a series of punitive laws, intended to end self-government in Massachusetts, but instead increased American support for the revolutionary cause.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1774, twelve of the Thirteen Colonies sent delegates to the First Continental Congress; the Province of Georgia joined in 1775.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The First Continental Congress began coordinating Patriot resistance through underground networks of committees largely built on the foundations of the Sons of Liberty network.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In August 1775, King George III proclaimed Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British attempted to disarm the colonists, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, sparking the Revolutionary War.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in May of 1775 and created the Continental Army, which then surrounded Boston, forcing the British to withdraw by sea in March 1776 and leaving Patriots in control in every colony.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority, and each colony created a state constitution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On July 2, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution, affirming their support for joint independence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On July 4, 1776 they unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence, famously proclaiming that "all men are created equal", having then evolved from a rebellion over British rights to a revolution based on universal rights.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Congress soon after began deliberating the Articles of Confederation, an effort to establish a multi-state self-governing coordinating body capable of negotiating international treaties and prosecuting the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Revolutionary War continued for another five years during which France ultimately entered, supporting the revolutionary cause.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On September 28, 1781, Washington commanded the Continental Army's capture of a British army under General Cornwallis at the Siege of Yorktown, leading to the collapse of King George's control of Parliament.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Consensus in Parliament soon shifted to the war ending on American terms.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On September 3, 1783, the British signed the Treaty of Paris, recognizing the sovereign independence of the United States, and ceding to the new nation nearly all the territory east of the Mississippi River and south of the Great Lakes.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The United States became the first nation to establish a federal republic with a written constitution based on the principles of universal natural rights, consent of the governed, and equality under the law, albeit with significant democratic limitations compared to later evolution of the concept.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution in Great Britain, it unofficially adopted a policy of "salutary neglect," whereby the Thirteen Colonies were largely left to govern themselves.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] This British policy reverted significantly after the French and Indian War.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British political establishment, especially after taking massive swaths of land from the former territories of New France, pursued a policy of greater control over colonial affairs, prompting the Thirteen Colonies to seek restoration of greater autonomy from Britain.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] After the American Revolution one Patriot, Capt.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Levi Preston of Danvers, Massachusetts, who was asked why the Americans rebelled against England, responded: "...we always had governed ourselves, and we always meant to.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies were established in the 17th century as part of the English Empire and became parts of the British Empire after the union of England and Scotland in 1707.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The development of a unique American identity can be traced to the English Civil War (1642–1651) and its aftermath.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In that period the Puritan colonies of New England supported the Commonwealth government responsible for the execution of King Charles I.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] After the Stuart Restoration of 1660, Massachusetts did not recognize Charles II as the legitimate king for more than a year after his coronation.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In King Philip's War (1675–1678), the New England colonies fought a coalition of a few Native American tribes without military assistance from England, thereby contributing to the development of a uniquely American identity separate from that of the British people.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In the 1680s, Charles and his brother, James II, attempted to bring New England under direct English control.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The colonists fiercely opposed this, and the Crown nullified their colonial charters in response.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1686, James finalized these efforts by consolidating the separate New England colonies along with New York and New Jersey into the Dominion of New England.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Edmund Andros was appointed royal governor and tasked with governing the new Dominion under his direct rule.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Colonial assemblies and town meetings were restricted, new local taxes were levied, and rights were abridged.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Dominion rule triggered bitter resentment throughout New England.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] When James tried to rule without Parliament, the English aristocracy removed him from power in the Glorious Revolution of 1688.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] This was followed by the 1689 Boston revolt, which overthrew Dominion rule.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Colonial governments reasserted their control after the revolt.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The new monarchs, William and Mary, granted new charters to the individual New England colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution, the British Empire became a constitutional monarchy with sovereignty in the King-in-Parliament.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Aristocrats inherited seats in the House of Lords, while the gentry and merchants controlled the elected House of Commons.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The king ruled through cabinet ministers who depended on majority support in the Commons to govern effectively.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] British subjects on both sides of the Atlantic proudly claimed that the unwritten British constitution, with its guarantees of the rights of Englishmen, protected personal liberty better than any other government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British constitution served as the model for colonial governments.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Crown appointed a royal governor in each colony to exercise executive power, usually also appointing a Governor's Council largely to act as an unelected upper chamber of the legislature.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Property owners elected a colonial assembly amongst themselves with powers to legislate and levy taxes, but the British government reserved the right to veto colonial legislation.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British government lacked the resources and information necessary for close supervision of the colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Instead, British officials negotiated and compromised with colonial leaders to gain compliance with imperial policies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The colonies defended themselves with provincial troops and colonial militias of locals, and the British government rarely sent military forces to America before 1755.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] According to historian Robert Middlekauff, "Americans had become almost completely self-governing" before the American Revolution, a practice that was consistent with the British monarchy's practice of salutary neglect.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] With little industry except shipbuilding, the colonies exported agricultural products in return for manufactured goods.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They also imported molasses, rum, and sugar from the British West Indies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1651, Parliament passed the first in a series of Navigation Acts, which restricted colonial trade with foreign countries.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British government pursued this policy of mercantilism in order to grow its economic and political power.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] According to mercantilism, the colonies existed for the mother country's economic benefit, and the colonists' economic needs were largely inconsequential.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies could trade with the rest of the empire but only ship certain commodities like tobacco to Britain.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Any European imports bound for British America had to first pass through an English port and pay customs duties.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Other laws regulated the developing colonial industries to prevent competition with industries in Britain, such as the Wool Act 1698, the Hat Act 1731, and the Iron Act 1750.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Colonial reactions to these policies were mixed.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Molasses Act 1733, for example, placed a duty of six pence per gallon upon foreign molasses imported into the colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] This act was particularly egregious to the New England colonists, who protested it as unconstitutional taxation without representation in the British parliament.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The act increased the smuggling of foreign molasses, and the British government ceased enforcement efforts after the 1740s.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, certain merchants and local industries benefited from the restrictions on foreign competition.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The limits on foreign-built ships greatly benefited the colonial shipbuilding industry, particularly in New England.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Some argue that the economic impact was minimal on the colonists, but the political friction that the acts triggered was more serious, as the merchants most directly affected were also the most politically active.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] During the French and Indian War (1754–1763), the British government fielded 45,000 soldiers, half British Regulars and half colonial volunteers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The colonies also contributed funds and materiel to the war effort; though, two-fifths of this spending was reimbursed by the British government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Great Britain defeated France and acquired that nation's territory east of the Mississippi River.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In order to allow approximately 1,500 politically well-connected British Army officers to remain on active duty in America with full pay after the war, the Bute ministry decided in early 1763 to permanently garrison 10,000 soldiers in North America.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Due to long-established English resistance to a standing army, stationing these officers in Great Britain during peacetime was a politically unacceptable alternative.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The excuse made for a standing army in America was defense against French troops stationed in the West Indies, and foreign populations in newly acquired territories (the French in Canada and the Spanish in Florida).
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In addition, British soldiers were supposed to help collect customs duties and prevent colonists from instigating conflict with Native Americans.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Instead, increased British migration beyond the Appalachian Mountains and Native American anger over the policies of General Jeffery Amherst caused Pontiac's War (1763–1766).
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In response, the Grenville ministry issued the Royal Proclamation of 1763, designating the territory between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River an Indian Reserve closed to colonial settlement.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Proclamation angered settlers, fur traders, and land speculators; however, it failed to stop westward migration.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Stationing troops in North America on a permanent basis would cost another £360,000 a year.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On a per capita basis, Grenville claimed Americans paid 1 shilling in taxes directly to the empire (not including local taxes) compared to 26 shillings paid by the English.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The enslaved, a near majority of the population in some colonies, did not pay any taxes and therefore skewed this comparison.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On March 9, 1764, Grenville proposed the Sugar Act, which was enacted by Parliament in April.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] It lowered the duty on foreign molasses from 6 pence to 3 pence per gallon.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Treasury believed it would generate £78,000.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] To ensure this money could be collected, the act strengthened efforts against smuggling.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials could choose whether to prosecute violators in colonial courts or vice admiralty courts.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Unlike colonial courts where there was a presumption of innocence and cases were decided by local juries who frequently acquitted accused smugglers, vice admiralty courts operated on a presumption of guilt and cases were decided by Crown-appointed judges.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On the same day he introduced the Sugar Act in Parliament, Grenville stated it might be necessary to levy stamp duties on the colonies to raise additional revenue, but he delayed action to give the colonies time to propose another way to raise the revenue.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Parliament passed the Stamp Act in March 1765, which imposed direct taxes on the colonies for the first time.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] All official documents, newspapers, almanacs, and pamphlets were required to have the stamps—even decks of playing cards.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The colonists did not object that the taxes were high; they were actually low.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They objected to their lack of representation in the Parliament, which gave them no voice concerning legislation that affected them, such as the tax, thereby violating the unwritten English constitution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] This grievance was overly simplified with the slogan "No taxation without representation".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Shortly following adoption of the Stamp Act, factions of the Sons of Liberty formed in each colony, and began using public demonstrations, boycotts, and threats of violence to ensure that the offending British policies became unenforceable.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In Boston, the Sons of Liberty burned the records of the vice admiralty court and looted the home of chief justice Thomas Hutchinson.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Several legislatures called for united action, and nine colonies sent delegates to the Stamp Act Congress in New York City in October.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Moderates led by John Dickinson drew up a Declaration of Rights and Grievances stating in part that the colonists were equal to all other British subjects and that, among other abuses, taxes passed without representation in Parliament violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Parliament at Westminster saw itself as the supreme lawmaking authority throughout the Empire and thus entitled to enact any legislation, including levying any tax, without colonial approval or even consultation.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They argued that the colonies were legally British corporations subordinate to the British Parliament.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Parliament insisted that the colonists effectively enjoyed a "virtual representation", as most British people did, since only a small minority of the British population were eligible to elect representatives to Parliament.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] However, Americans such as James Otis maintained that there was no one in Parliament responsible specifically to any colonial constituency, so they were not "virtually represented" by anyone in Parliament.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Rockingham government came to power in July 1765, and Parliament debated whether to repeal the stamp tax or to send an army to enforce it.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin appeared before them to make the case for repeal, explaining that the colonies had spent heavily in manpower, money, and blood defending the empire, and that further taxes to pay for those wars were unjust and might bring about a rebellion.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Parliament agreed and repealed the tax on February 21, 1766, but they insisted in the Declaratory Act of March 1766 that they retained full power to make laws for the colonies "in all cases whatsoever".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The repeal nonetheless caused widespread celebrations in the colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, the British Parliament passed the Townshend Acts, which placed duties on several staple goods, including paper, glass, and tea, and established a Board of Customs in Boston to more rigorously execute trade regulations.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The new taxes were enacted on the belief that Americans only objected to internal taxes and not to external taxes such as custom duties.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] John Dickinson however, in his widely read pamphlet *Letters from a Farmer in Pennsylvania*, argued against the constitutionality of the acts because their purpose was to raise revenue and not to regulate trade.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Colonists responded to the taxes by organizing new boycotts of British goods.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] These boycotts were less effective, however, as the goods taxed by the Townshend Acts were widely used.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In February 1768, the Assembly of Massachusetts Bay Colony issued a circular letter to the other colonies urging them to coordinate resistance.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The governor dissolved the assembly when it refused to rescind the letter.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In June 1768 a riot broke out in Boston over the seizure of the sloop *Liberty*, owned by John Hancock, for alleged smuggling.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials were forced to flee, prompting the British to deploy troops to Boston.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] A Boston town meeting declared that no obedience was due to parliamentary laws and called for the convening of a convention.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] A convention assembled but only issued a mild protest before dissolving itself.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In January 1769, Parliament responded to the unrest by reactivating the Treason Act 1543 which called for subjects outside the realm to face trials for treason in England.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The governor of Massachusetts was instructed to collect evidence of said treason, and the threat caused widespread outrage, though it was not carried out.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On March 5, 1770, a large crowd gathered around a group of British soldiers on a Boston street.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The crowd grew threatening, throwing snowballs, rocks, and debris at them.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] There was no order to fire, but the soldiers panicked and fired into the crowd.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They hit 11 people; three civilians died of wounds at the scene of the shooting, and two died shortly after.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The event quickly came to be called the Boston Massacre.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The soldiers were tried and acquitted (defended by American patriot John Adams), but the widespread descriptions soon began to turn colonial sentiment against the British.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] This accelerated the downward spiral in the relationship between Britain and the province of Massachusetts, and other colonies were becoming increasingly empathetic.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] A new ministry under Lord North came to power in 1770, and Parliament repealed most of the Townshend duties, except the tax on tea.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] This temporarily resolved the crisis, and the boycott of British goods largely ceased, with only the more radical patriots such as Samuel Adams continuing to agitate.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In June 1772, American patriots, including John Brown, burned a British warship that had been vigorously enforcing unpopular trade regulations, in what became known as the *Gaspee* Affair.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The affair was investigated for possible treason, but no action was taken.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1773, private letters were published in which Massachusetts Governor Thomas Hutchinson claimed that the colonists could not enjoy all English liberties, and in which Lieutenant Governor Andrew Oliver called for the direct payment of colonial officials, which had been paid by local authorities.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] This would have reduced the influence of colonial representatives over their government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The letters' contents were used as evidence of a systematic plot against American rights, and discredited Hutchinson in the eyes of the people; the colonial Assembly petitioned for his recall.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin, postmaster general for the colonies, acknowledged that he leaked the letters, which led to him being removed from his position.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] From Boston Samuel Adams set about creating new Committees of Correspondence, built largely on the foundations of the underground Sons of Liberty network, linking Patriots in all 13 colonies and eventually providing the framework for a provisional government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Virginia, the largest colony, set up its Committee of Correspondence in early 1773, on which Patrick Henry and Thomas Jefferson served.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] A total of about 7,000 to 8,000 Patriots served on these Committees; Loyalists were excluded.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The committees became the leaders of the American resistance to British actions, and later largely determined the war effort at the state and local level.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] When the First Continental Congress resolved to boycott British products, the colonial and local Committees took charge, examining merchant records and publishing the names of merchants who attempted to defy the boycott by importing British goods.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, Parliament passed the Tea Act lowering the price of taxed tea exported to the colonies, to help the British East India Company undersell smuggled untaxed Dutch tea.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Special consignees were appointed to sell the tea to bypass colonial merchants.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The act was opposed by those who resisted the taxes and also by smugglers who stood to lose business.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In every colony demonstrators warned merchants not to bring in tea that included the hated new tax.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In most instances, the consignees were forced by the Americans to resign and the tea was turned back, but Massachusetts governor Hutchinson refused to allow Boston merchants to give in to pressure.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] A town meeting in Boston determined that the tea would not be landed, and ignored a demand from the governor to disperse.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On December 16, 1773, a group of men, led by Samuel Adams and dressed to evoke the appearance of Indigenous people, boarded the ships of the East India Company and dumped £10,000 worth of tea from their holds (approximately £636,000 in 2008) into Boston Harbor.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Decades later, this event became known as the Boston Tea Party and remains a significant part of American patriotic lore.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British government responded by passing four laws that came to be known as the Intolerable Acts, further darkening colonial opinion towards England.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The first was the Massachusetts Government Act which altered the Massachusetts charter and restricted town meetings.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The second was the Administration of Justice Act which ordered that all British soldiers to be tried were to be arraigned in Britain, not in the colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The third was the Boston Port Act, which closed the port of Boston until the British had been compensated for the tea lost in the Boston Tea Party.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The fourth was the Quartering Act of 1774, which allowed royal governors to house British troops in the homes of citizens without permission of the owner.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In response, "Starting in August 1774, each time a court was slated to meet in some Massachusetts town, great numbers of angry citizens made sure it did not".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The next month Patriots issued the Suffolk Resolves and formed an alternative shadow government known as the Massachusetts Provincial Congress, which began training militia outside British-occupied Boston.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In September 1774, the First Continental Congress convened in Pennsylvania, consisting of representatives from each colony, to serve as a vehicle for deliberation and collective action.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] During secret debates, conservative Joseph Galloway proposed the creation of a colonial Parliament that would be able to approve or disapprove acts of the British Parliament, but his idea was tabled in a vote of 6 to 5 and was subsequently removed from the record.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Congress called for a boycott beginning on December 1, 1774, of all British goods; it was enforced by new local committees authorized by the Congress that were largely built upon the earlier Committees of Correspondence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] It also began coordinating Patriot resistance by militias in each colony, including many veterans who had gained military experience in the French and Indian War.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] For the first time, the Patriots were armed and unified against Parliament.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] King George III declared Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion in February 1775 and the British garrison received orders to seize the rebels' weapons and arrest their leaders, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord on April 19, 1775.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Patriots assembled a militia 15,000 strong and laid siege to Boston, occupied by 6500 British soldiers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in Philadelphia on June 14, 1775.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The congress was divided on the best course of action.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They authorized formation of the Continental Army, appointing George Washington as its commander-in-chief, while producing the Olive Branch Petition in which they attempted to come to an accord with King George.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The king, however, would issue a Proclamation of Rebellion in August which declared that all the states were "in rebellion" and the members of Congress were traitors.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, the Battle of Bunker Hill on June 17, 1775 was a British victory—but at a great cost: about 1,000 British casualties from a garrison of about 6,000, as compared to 500 American casualties from a much larger force.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In the winter of 1775, the Americans invaded northeastern Quebec under generals Benedict Arnold and Richard Montgomery, expecting to rally sympathetic colonists there.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The attack was a failure; many Americans were killed, captured, or died of smallpox.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Following the Battle of Bunker Hill in June 1775, the Patriots had control of Massachusetts outside Boston's city limits, and the Loyalists suddenly found themselves on the defensive with no protection from the British army.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In each of the Thirteen Colonies, American patriots overthrew their existing governments, closed courts, and drove out British colonial officials.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They held elected conventions and established their own legislatures, which existed outside any legal parameters established by the British.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] New constitutions were drawn up in each state to supersede royal charters.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They proclaimed that they were now *states*, no longer *colonies*.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On January 5, 1776, New Hampshire ratified the first state constitution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] New Jersey, South Carolina, and Virginia created their constitutions before July 4.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Rhode Island and Connecticut simply took their existing royal charters and deleted all references to the Crown.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The new states were all committed to republicanism, with no inherited offices.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The radical provisions of Pennsylvania's constitution lasted 14 years.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1790, conservatives gained power in the state legislature, called a new constitutional convention, and rewrote the constitution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The new constitution substantially reduced universal male suffrage, gave the governor veto power and patronage appointment authority, and added an upper house with substantial wealth qualifications to the unicameral legislature.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Thomas Paine called it a constitution unworthy of America.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In March 1776, aided by the fortification of Dorchester Heights with cannons recently captured at Fort Ticonderoga, the Continental Army led by George Washington forced the British to evacuate Boston.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries now fully controlled all thirteen states and ready to declare joint independence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] There still were many Loyalists, but they were no longer in control anywhere by July 1776, and all of the royal officials had fled.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In April 1776, the North Carolina Provincial Congress issued the Halifax Resolves explicitly authorizing its delegates to vote for independence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] By June, nine state legislatures supported independence from Britain, and Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, and New York followed.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Richard Henry Lee was instructed by the Virginia legislature to propose independence, and he did so on June 7, 1776.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Gathered at Pennsylvania State House in Philadelphia, later renamed Independence Hall, 56 of the nation's Founding Fathers representing the United Colonies adopted and issued to King George III the Declaration of Independence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] It had been drafted largely by Thomas Jefferson, and was edited and presented by the Committee of Five which was charged with authoring it.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Congress struck several provisions of the Committee's draft, and then adopted it unanimously on July 4.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Declaration embodied universal rights expressed through the political philosophies of liberalism and republicanism, rejected monarchy and aristocracy, and famously proclaimed that "all men are created equal".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] What had begun as a rebellion demanding the rights of Englishmen had now evolved into a revolution to overthrow and replace the political and social order in America based on universal rights.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] With the new state constitutions and the issuance of the Declaration of Independence, each former colony began operating as an independent and sovereign state.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The next step was to form a union to facilitate international relations and alliances.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On November 5, 1777, the Congress approved the Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union and sent it to each state for ratification.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Congress immediately began operating under the Articles' terms, providing a structure of shared sovereignty during prosecution of the Revolutionary War.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Articles were fully ratified on March 1, 1781.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] At that point, the Continental Congress was dissolved and a new government of the United States in Congress Assembled took its place the following day, with Samuel Huntington leading the Congress as presiding officer.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] It remained a unicameral body, where each state retained one vote.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] According to British historian Jeremy Black, the British had significant advantages, including a highly trained army, the world's largest navy, and an efficient system of public finance that could easily fund the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] However, they seriously misunderstood the depth of support for the American Patriot position, misinterpreting the situation as merely a large-scale riot.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In the Siege of Boston, Washington forced the British out of the city in the spring of 1776, and neither the British nor the Loyalists controlled any significant areas.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British, however, were amassing forces at their naval base at Halifax, Nova Scotia.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They returned in force in July 1776, landing in New York and defeating Washington's Continental Army toe-to-toe in August at the Battle of Brooklyn, the largest battle of the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Following that victory, and poised to take New York City, they requested a meeting with representatives from Congress to negotiate an end to hostilities.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] A delegation including John Adams and Benjamin Franklin met British admiral Richard Howe on Staten Island in New York Harbor on September 11 in what became known as the Staten Island Peace Conference.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Howe demanded that the Americans retract the Declaration of Independence, which they refused to do, and negotiations ended.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British then seized New York City and nearly captured Washington's army.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They made the city their main political and military base of operations, holding the strategic harbor and port until November 1783.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The city became the destination for Loyalist refugees and a focal point of Washington's intelligence network.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British also took New Jersey, pushing the Continental Army into Pennsylvania.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Washington crossed the Delaware River back into New Jersey in a surprise attack in late December 1776 and defeated the Hessian and British garrisons at Trenton and Princeton, thereby regaining control of most of New Jersey.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The victories gave an important boost to Patriots at a time when morale was flagging and enlistments were ending, and they have become iconic events of the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1777, the British sent Burgoyne's invasion force from Canada south through New York with the aim of isolating New England to the east, which the British perceived as the primary source of agitation.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In anticipation of a coordinated British attack on the *de facto* revolutionary capital of Philadelphia, the Continental Congress was forced to temporarily depart Philadelphia in September for Baltimore, where they continued deliberations.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Rather than move north to support Burgoyne, the British army in New York City in fact went to Philadelphia in a major case of mis-coordination, capturing it from Washington.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The invasion army from Canada was much too slow and became trapped in northern New York state.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] It surrendered to the Americans after the Battles of Saratoga in October 1777.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] From early October 1777 until November 15, a siege distracted British troops at Fort Mifflin, Pennsylvania and allowed Washington time to preserve the Continental Army by safely leading his troops to harsh winter quarters at Valley Forge, some 35 miles from Philadelphia.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On August 23, 1775, George III declared Americans to be traitors to the Crown if they took up arms against royal authority.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] There were thousands of British and Hessian soldiers in American hands following their surrender at the Battles of Saratoga.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Lord Germain took a hard line, but the British generals on American soil never held treason trials, and instead treated captured American soldiers as prisoners of war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The dilemma was that tens of thousands of Loyalists were under American control and American retaliation would have been easy.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British built much of their strategy around using these Loyalists.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British maltreated the prisoners whom they held, resulting in more American deaths in the prisons than all the American battlefield mortalities, combined.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] At the end of the war, both sides released their surviving prisoners.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The capture of a British army at Saratoga encouraged the French to formally enter the war in support of Congress, and Benjamin Franklin negotiated a permanent military alliance in early 1778; France thus became the first foreign nation to officially recognize the Declaration of Independence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On February 6, 1778, the United States and France signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce and the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] William Pitt spoke out in Parliament urging Britain to make peace with the Americans and to unite against France, while British politicians who had sympathized with colonial grievances now turned against the Americans for allying with Britain's rival and enemy.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Spanish and the Dutch became allies of the French in 1779 and 1780 respectively, forcing the British to fight a global war without major allies, and requiring it to slip through a combined blockade of the Atlantic.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Dutch Republic, also at war with Britain, was the next country after France to sign a treaty with the United States, on October 8, 1782.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On April 3, 1783, Ambassador Extraordinary Gustaf Philip Creutz, representing King Gustav III of Sweden, and Benjamin Franklin, signed a Treaty of Amity and Commerce with the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Britain began to view the American Revolutionary War as merely one front in a wider war, and the British chose to withdraw troops from America to reinforce the British colonies in the Caribbean, which were under threat of Spanish or French invasion.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] British commander Sir Henry Clinton evacuated Philadelphia and returned to New York City.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Washington intercepted him in the Battle of Monmouth Court House, the last major battle fought in the north.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] After an inconclusive engagement, the British retreated to New York City.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The northern war subsequently became a stalemate, as the focus of attention shifted to the smaller southern theater.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British Royal Navy blockaded ports and held New York City for the duration of the war, and other cities for brief periods, but failed in their effort to destroy Washington's forces.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British strategy now concentrated on a campaign in the southern states.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Due to a lack of regular troops at their disposal compared to the Americans, the British commanders saw the "southern strategy" as a more viable plan.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They perceived the Southern Colonies as strongly Loyalist, with a large population of recent British immigrants, and large numbers of slaves who might be tempted to run away from their Patriot masters to join the British and gain their freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Beginning in late December 1778, the British captured Savannah and controlled the Georgia coastline.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In 1780, they launched a fresh invasion and took Charleston.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] A significant victory at the Battle of Camden meant that royal forces soon controlled most of Georgia and South Carolina.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British set up a network of forts inland, hoping that the Loyalists would rally to the flag.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Not enough Loyalists turned out, however, and the British had to fight their way north into North Carolina and Virginia with a severely weakened army.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Behind them, much of the territory that they had already captured dissolved into a chaotic guerrilla war, fought predominantly between bands of Loyalists and American militia, which negated many of the gains that the British had previously made.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British army under Cornwallis marched to Yorktown, Virginia, where they expected to be rescued by a British fleet.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The fleet did arrive, but so did a larger French fleet.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The French were victorious in the Battle of the Chesapeake, and the British fleet returned to New York for reinforcements, leaving Cornwallis trapped.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] In October 1781, the British surrendered their second invading army of the war under a siege by the combined French and Continental armies commanded by Washington.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Washington did not know if or when the British might reopen hostilities after Yorktown.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] They still had 26,000 troops occupying New York City, Charleston, and Savannah, together with a powerful fleet.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The French army and navy departed, so the Americans were on their own in 1782–83.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The American treasury was empty, and the unpaid soldiers were growing restive, almost to the point of mutiny or possible coup d'etat.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Washington dispelled the unrest among officers of the Newburgh Conspiracy in 1783, and Congress subsequently created the promise of a five years bonus for all officers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Historians continue to debate whether the odds were long or short for American victory.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Ferling says that the odds were so long that the American victory was "almost a miracle".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, Joseph Ellis says that the odds favored the Americans, and asks whether there ever was any realistic chance for the British to win.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] He argues that this opportunity came only once, in the summer of 1776, where Admiral Howe and his brother General Howe "missed several opportunities to destroy the Continental Army ....
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Chance, luck, and even the vagaries of the weather played crucial roles." Ellis's point is that the strategic and tactical decisions of the Howes were fatally flawed because they underestimated the challenges posed by the Patriots.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Ellis concludes that, once the Howe brothers failed, the opportunity "would never come again" for a British victory.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Public support for the conflict had never been strong in Britain, where many sympathized with the Americans, but now it reached a new low.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] King George wanted to fight on, but his supporters lost control of Parliament and the British launched no further offensives in America on the eastern seaboard.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] During negotiations in Paris, the American delegation discovered that France supported American independence but no territorial gains, hoping to confine the new nation to the area east of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The Americans opened direct secret negotiations with London, cutting out the French.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] British Prime Minister Lord Shelburne was in charge of the British negotiations, and he saw a chance to make the United States a valuable economic partner, facilitating trade and investment opportunities.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The US obtained all the land east of the Mississippi River, including southern Canada below the Great Lakes, but Spain took control of Florida from the British.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] It gained fishing rights off Canadian coasts, and agreed to allow British merchants and Loyalists to recover their property.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] Prime Minister Shelburne foresaw highly profitable two-way trade between Britain and the rapidly growing United States, which did come to pass.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The blockade was lifted and American merchants were free to trade with any nation anywhere in the world.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] The British largely abandoned their Indigenous allies, who were not a party to this treaty and did not recognize it until they were defeated militarily by the United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p01] However, the British did sell them munitions and maintained forts in American territory until the Jay Treaty of 1795.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Britain's war against the Americans, the French, and the Spanish cost about £100 million.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Treasury borrowed 40 percent of the money that it needed.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Britain had a sophisticated financial system based on the wealth of thousands of landowners who supported the government, together with banks and financiers in London.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In London the British had relatively little difficulty financing their war, keeping their suppliers and soldiers paid, and hiring tens of thousands of German soldiers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In sharp contrast, Congress and the American states had no end of difficulty financing the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In 1775, there was at most 12 million dollars in gold in the colonies, not nearly enough to cover current transactions, let alone finance a major war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The British made the situation much worse by imposing a tight blockade on every American port, which cut off almost all trade.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] One partial solution was to rely on volunteer support from militiamen and donations from patriotic citizens.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Another was to delay actual payments, pay soldiers and suppliers in depreciated currency, and promise that it would be made good after the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Indeed, the soldiers and officers were given land grants in 1783 to cover the wages that they had earned but had not been paid during the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Starting in 1776, the Congress sought to raise money by loans from wealthy individuals, promising to redeem the bonds after the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The bonds were redeemed in 1791 at face value, but the scheme raised little money because Americans had little specie, and many of the richest merchants were supporters of the Crown.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Beginning in 1777, Congress repeatedly asked the states to provide money, but it had no system of taxation to require funds, and the states were of little help.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, Congress was making requisitions for specific supplies of corn, beef, pork, and other necessities, an inefficient system which barely kept the army alive.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Congress used four main methods to cover the cost of the war, which cost about 66 million dollars in specie (gold and silver).
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Significantly, the French secretly supplied the Americans with money, gunpowder, and munitions to weaken Great Britain; the subsidies continued when France entered the war in 1778, and the French government and Paris bankers lent large sums to the American war effort.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Congress also made issues of paper money, known colloquially as "Continental Dollars", in 1775–1780 and in 1780–1781.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The first issue amounted to 242 million dollars.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] This paper money would supposedly be redeemed for state taxes, but the holders were eventually paid off in 1791 at the rate of one cent on the dollar.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, the paper money was so devalued that the phrase "not worth a Continental" became synonymous with valueless.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The skyrocketing inflation was a hardship on the few people who had fixed incomes, but 90 percent of the people were farmers and were not directly affected by it.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Debtors benefited by paying off their debts with depreciated paper.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The greatest burden was borne by the soldiers of the Continental Army whose wages were usually paid late and depreciated in value every month, weakening their morale and adding to the hardships of their families.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The national government did not have a strong leader in financial matters until 1781, when Robert Morris was named Superintendent of Finance of the United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Morris used a French loan in 1782 to set up the private Bank of North America to finance the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] He reduced the civil list, saved money by using competitive bidding for contracts, tightened accounting procedures, and demanded the national government's full share of money and supplies from the individual states.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The war ended in 1783 and was followed by a period of slow economic recovery that accompanied the end of mercantilism and the resumption and expansion of worldwide trade.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The national government was still operating under the Articles of Confederation and settled the issue of the western territories, which the states ceded to Congress.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] American settlers moved rapidly into those areas, with Vermont, Kentucky, and Tennessee becoming states in the 1790s.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] However, the national government had no authority to tax, no money either to pay the war debts owed to European nations and the private banks, or to pay Americans who had been given millions of dollars of promissory notes for supplies during the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Nationalists led by Washington, Alexander Hamilton, and other veterans feared that the new nation was too fragile to withstand an international war, or even the repetition of internal revolts such as the Shays's Rebellion of 1786 in Massachusetts.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They convinced the Congress of the Confederation to call the Philadelphia Convention in 1787.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Convention adopted a new Constitution which provided for a republic with authority to tax and a much stronger national government in a federal framework, including an effective executive in a check-and-balance system with the judiciary and legislature.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Constitution was ratified in 1788, after a fierce debate in the states over the proposed new government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The new administration under President George Washington took office in New York in March 1789 and the new bicameral Congress of the United States was seated.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] James Madison spearheaded Congressional legislation proposing amendments to the Constitution as assurances to those cautious about federal power, guaranteeing many of the inalienable rights that formed a foundation for the revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Rhode Island was the final state to ratify the Constitution in 1790, the first ten amendments were ratified in 1791 and became known as the United States Bill of Rights.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The national debt fell into three categories after the Revolutionary War.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The first was the $12 million owed to foreigners, mostly money borrowed from France.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] There was general agreement to pay the foreign debts at full value.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The national government owed $40 million and state governments owed $25 million to Americans who had sold food, horses, and supplies to the Patriot forces.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] There were also other debts which consisted of promissory notes issued during the war to soldiers, merchants, and farmers who accepted these payments on the premise that the new nation would create a government that would pay these debts eventually.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Americans struggled to pay off the French loans; they ceased making interest payments to France in 1785 and defaulted on installments due in 1787.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, however, they resumed regular payments on their debts to the French.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The war expenses of the individual states added up to $114 million, compared to $37 million by the central government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, Congress combined the remaining state debts with the foreign and domestic debts into one national debt totaling $80 million at the recommendation of first Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Everyone received face value for wartime certificates, so that the national honor would be sustained and the national credit established.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Accounts with the French government were settled in 1795 when James Swan, an American banker acting as agent for France, helped refinance the United States’ remaining debt to France.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The American government issued bonds in the amount of the remaining debt and sold them publicly, with the proceeds going to France through Swan.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The United States no longer owed money to foreign governments, although it continued to owe money to private investors both in the United States and in Europe..
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] This allowed the young United States to place itself on a sound financial footing.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The population of the Thirteen States was not homogeneous in political views and attitudes.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Loyalties and allegiances varied widely within regions and communities and even within families, and sometimes shifted during the Revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The American Enlightenment was a critical precursor of the American Revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Chief among the ideas of the American Enlightenment were the concepts of natural law, natural rights, consent of the governed, self-determination, equality under the law, liberalism, republicanism, and intolerance of political corruption.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] A growing number of American colonists embraced these views and fostered an intellectual environment which led to a new sense of political and social identity.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] John Locke is often referred to as "the philosopher of the American Revolution" due to his work in the Social Contract and Natural Rights theories that underpinned the Revolution's political ideology.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Locke's *Two Treatises of Government* published in 1689 was especially influential.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] He argued that all humans were created equally free, and governments therefore needed the "consent of the governed".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] This contrasted and conflicted sharply with the British system of inherited political power and hierarchy.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In late eighteenth-century America, belief was still widespread in "equality by creation" and "rights by creation".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Locke's ideas on liberty influenced the political thinking of English writers such as John Trenchard, Thomas Gordon, and Benjamin Hoadly, whose political ideas in turn also had a strong influence on the American Patriots.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] His work also inspired symbols used in the American Revolution such as the "Appeal to Heaven" found on the Pine Tree Flag, which alludes to Locke's concept of the right of revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The theory of the social contract influenced the belief among many of the Founders that the right of the people to overthrow their leaders, should those leaders betray the historic rights of Englishmen, was one of the "natural rights" of man.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Americans heavily relied on Montesquieu's analysis of the wisdom of the "balanced" British Constitution (mixed government) in writing the state and national constitutions.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The American interpretation of republicanism was inspired by the Whig party in Great Britain which openly criticized the corruption within the British government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Americans were increasingly embracing republican values, seeing Britain as corrupt and hostile to American interests.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Radical Whig ideology profoundly influenced colonial American political philosophy with its love of liberty and opposition to tyrannical government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The American revolutionaries associated political corruption with ostentatious luxury and inherited aristocracy.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Founding Fathers were strong advocates of republican values, particularly Samuel Adams, Patrick Henry, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Thomas Jefferson, Thomas Paine, George Washington, James Madison, and Alexander Hamilton, which required men to put civic duty ahead of their personal desires.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Men were honor bound by civic obligation to be prepared and willing to fight for the rights and liberties of their countrymen.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Protestant churches that had separated from the Church of England, called "dissenters", were the "school of democracy", in the words of historian Patricia Bonomi.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Before the Revolution, the Southern Colonies and three of the New England Colonies had official established churches: Congregational in Massachusetts Bay, Connecticut, and New Hampshire, and the Church of England in Maryland, Virginia, North-Carolina, South Carolina, and Georgia.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The colonies of New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, and the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations had no officially established churches.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] John Witherspoon, who was considered a "new light" Presbyterian, wrote widely circulated sermons linking the American Revolution to the teachings of the Bible.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Throughout the colonies, dissenting Protestant ministers from the Congregational, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches preached Revolutionary themes in their sermons while most Church of England clergymen preached loyalty to the king, the titular head of the English state church.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Religious motivation for fighting tyranny transcended socioeconomic lines.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Historian Bernard Bailyn argues that the evangelicalism of the era challenged traditional notions of natural hierarchy by preaching that the Bible teaches all men are equal, and the true value of a man therefore lies in his moral behavior, not in his class.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Bailyn, on the other hand, denies that religion played such a critical role.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Alan Heimert argues that New Light anti-authoritarianism was essential to furthering democracy in colonial American society, and set the stage for a confrontation with British monarchical and aristocratic rule.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Historians in the early 20th century such as J.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Franklin Jameson examined the class composition of the Patriot cause, looking for evidence of a class war inside the revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] More recent historians have largely abandoned that interpretation, emphasizing instead the high level of ideological unity.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Both Loyalists and Patriots were a "mixed lot", but ideological demands always came first.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The revolution became a personal issue for the king, fueled by his growing belief that British leniency would be taken as weakness by the Americans.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] He also sincerely believed that he was defending Britain's constitution against usurpers, rather than opposing patriots fighting for their natural rights.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] King George III is often accused of obstinately trying to keep Great Britain at war with the revolutionaries in America, despite the opinions of his own ministers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Later historians defend George by saying in the context of the times no king would willingly surrender such a large territory, and his conduct was far less ruthless than contemporary monarchs in Europe.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] After the surrender of a British army at Saratoga, both Parliament and the British people were largely in favor of the war; recruitment ran at high levels and although political opponents were vocal, they remained a small minority.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] With the early setbacks in America, Lord North asked to transfer power to Lord Chatham, whom he thought more capable, but George refused to do so; he suggested instead that Chatham serve as a subordinate minister in North's administration, but Chatham refused.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Lord North was allied to the "King's Friends" faction in Parliament and believed George III had the right to exercise extensive powers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In early 1778, Britain's chief rival France signed a treaty of alliance with the United States, and the confrontation soon escalated from a "rebellion" to something that has been characterized as "world war".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The French fleet was able to outrun the British naval blockade of the Mediterranean and sailed to North America.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The conflict now affected North America, Europe and India.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The United States and France were joined by Spain in 1779 and the Dutch Republic, while Britain had no major allies of its own, except for the Loyalist minority in America and German auxiliaries (i.e.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Lord Gower and Lord Weymouth both resigned from the government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Lord North again requested that he also be allowed to resign, but he stayed in office at George III's insistence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Opposition to the costly war was increasing, and in June 1780 contributed to disturbances in London known as the Gordon riots.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] As late as the Siege of Charleston in 1780, Loyalists could still believe in their eventual victory, as British troops inflicted defeats on the Continental forces at the Battle of Camden and the Battle of Guilford Court House.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In late 1781, the news of Cornwallis's surrender at the siege of Yorktown reached London; Lord North's parliamentary support ebbed away and he resigned the following year.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The king drafted an abdication notice, which was never delivered, finally accepted the defeat in North America, and authorized peace negotiations.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Treaties of Paris, by which Britain recognized the sovereignty of the United States and returned Florida to Spain, were signed in 1782 and 1783 respectively.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In early 1783, George III privately conceded "America is lost!" He reflected that the former colonies had developed into Britain's "successful rivals" in commercial trade and fishing as the United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] When John Adams was appointed American Minister to London in 1785, George had become resigned to the new relationship between his country and the former colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Those who fought for independence were called "Revolutionaries", "Continentals", "Rebels", "Patriots", "Whigs", "Congress-men", or "Americans" during and after the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They included a full range of social and economic classes but were unanimous regarding the need to defend the natural rights of Americans and uphold the principles of republicanism in rejecting monarchy and aristocracy, while emphasizing civic virtue by citizens.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The signers of the Declaration of Independence were overwhelmingly—with definite exceptions—well-educated, of British stock, and of the Protestant faith.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Newspapers were strongholds of patriotism (although there were a few Loyalist papers) and printed many pamphlets, announcements, patriotic letters, and pronouncements.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] According to historian Robert Calhoon, 40 to 45 percent of the white population in the Thirteen Colonies supported the Patriots' cause, 15 to 20 percent supported the Loyalists, and the remainder were neutral or kept a low profile.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Mark Lender concludes that ordinary people became insurgents against the British because they held a sense of rights which the British were violating, rights that stressed local autonomy, fair dealing, and government by consent.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They were highly sensitive to the issue of tyranny, which they saw manifested in the British response to the Boston Tea Party.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The arrival in Boston of the British Army heightened their sense of violated rights, leading to rage and demands for revenge.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They had faith that God was on their side.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Patriots viewed independence as a means to gain freedom from British oppression and initially to reassert their rights on par with subjects in Britain.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Most yeomen farmers, craftsmen, and small merchants joined the Patriot cause to demand more political equality.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They were especially successful in Pennsylvania but less so in New England, where John Adams attacked Thomas Paine's *Common Sense* for the "absurd democratical notions" that it proposed.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Thomas Paine published his pamphlet *Common Sense* in January 1776, after the Revolution had started.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] It was widely distributed and often read aloud in taverns, contributing significantly to concurrently spreading the ideas of republicanism and liberalism, bolstering enthusiasm for separation from Great Britain, and encouraging recruitment for the Continental Army.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Paine presented the Revolution as the solution for Americans alarmed by the threat of tyranny.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The consensus of scholars is that about 15 to 20 percent of the white population remained loyal to the British Crown.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Those who actively supported the king were known at the time as "Loyalists", "Tories", or "King's men".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Loyalists never controlled territory unless the British Army occupied it.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They were typically older, less willing to break with old loyalties, and often connected to the Church of England; they included many established merchants with strong business connections throughout the Empire, as well as royal officials such as Thomas Hutchinson of Boston.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In the mid-20th century, historian Leonard Woods Labaree identified eight characteristics of the Loyalists that made them essentially conservative, opposite to the characteristics of the Patriots.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists tended to feel that resistance to the Crown was morally wrong, while the Patriots thought that morality was on their side.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists were alienated when the Patriots resorted to violence, such as burning houses and tarring and feathering.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists wanted to take a centrist position and resisted the Patriots' demand to declare their opposition to the Crown.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Numerous Loyalists had maintained strong and long-standing relations with Britain, especially merchants in port cities such as New York and Boston.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists felt that independence was bound to come eventually, but they were fearful that revolution might lead to anarchy, tyranny, or mob rule.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In contrast, the prevailing attitude among Patriots was a desire to seize the initiative.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Labaree also contended that Loyalists were pessimists who lacked the confidence in the future displayed by the Patriots.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] There were "tens of thousands" of Black Loyalists, enslaved African Americans who escaped to British lines and supported Britain's cause via several means.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Many of them died from disease, but the survivors were evacuated by the British to their remaining colonies in North America.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The revolution could divide families, such as William Franklin, son of Benjamin Franklin and royal governor of the Province of New Jersey who remained loyal to the Crown throughout the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Recent immigrants who had not been fully Americanized were also inclined to support the King.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] After the war, the great majority of the half-million Loyalists remained in America and resumed normal lives.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Some became prominent American leaders, such as Samuel Seabury.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Approximately 46,000 Loyalists relocated to Canada; others moved to Britain (7,000), Florida, or the West Indies (9,000).
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The exiles represented approximately two percent of the total population of the colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Nearly all Black Loyalists left for Nova Scotia, Florida, or England, where they could remain free.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists who left the South in 1783 took thousands of enslaved persons with them as they fled to the British West Indies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] A minority of uncertain size tried to stay neutral in the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Most kept a low profile, but the Quakers were the most important group to speak out for neutrality, especially in Pennsylvania.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Quakers continued to do business with the British even after the war began, and they were accused of supporting British rule, "contrivers and authors of seditious publications" critical of the revolutionary cause.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Most Quakers remained neutral, although a sizeable number participated to some degree.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Women contributed to the American Revolution in many ways and were involved on both sides.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Formal politics did not include women, but ordinary domestic behaviors became charged with political significance as Patriot women confronted a war which permeated all aspects of political, civil, and domestic life.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They participated by boycotting British goods, spying on the British, following armies as they marched, washing, cooking, and mending for soldiers, delivering secret messages, and even fighting disguised as men in a few cases, such as Deborah Samson.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Mercy Otis Warren held meetings in her house and cleverly attacked Loyalists with her creative plays and histories.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Many women also acted as nurses and helpers, tending to the soldiers' wounds and buying and selling goods for them.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Some of these camp followers even participated in combat, such as Madam John Turchin who led her husband's regiment into battle.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Above all, women continued the agricultural work at home to feed their families and the armies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They maintained their families during their husbands' absences and sometimes after their deaths.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] American women were integral to the success of the boycott of British goods, as the boycotted items were largely household articles such as tea and cloth.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Women had to return to knitting goods and to spinning and weaving their own cloth—skills that had fallen into disuse.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In 1769, the women of Boston produced 40,000 skeins of yarn, and 180 women in Middletown, Massachusetts wove 20,522 yards (18,765 m) of cloth.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Many women gathered food, money, clothes, and other supplies during the war to help the soldiers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] A woman's loyalty to her husband could become an open political act, especially for women in America committed to men who remained loyal to the King.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Legal divorce, usually rare, was granted to Patriot women whose husbands supported the King.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In early 1776, France set up a major program of aid to the Americans, and the Spanish secretly added funds.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Each country spent one million "livres tournaises" to buy munitions.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] A dummy corporation run by Pierre Beaumarchais concealed their activities.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots obtained some munitions from the Dutch Republic as well, through the French and Spanish ports in the West Indies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Heavy expenditures and a weak taxation system pushed France toward bankruptcy.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In 1777, Charles François Adrien le Paulmier, Chevalier d'Annemours, acting as a secret agent for France, made sure General George Washington was privy to his mission.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] He followed Congress around for the next two years, reporting what he observed back to France.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Treaty of Alliance between the French and the Americans followed in 1778, which led to more French money, matériel and troops being sent to the United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Spain did not officially recognize the United States, but it was a French ally and it separately declared war on Britain on June 21, 1779.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Bernardo de Gálvez, general of the Spanish forces in New Spain bordering the Americans, also served as governor of Louisiana.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] He led an expedition of colonial troops to capture Florida from the British and to keep open a vital conduit for supplies going to the Americans.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Ethnic Germans served on both sides of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] As George III was also the Elector of Hanover, many supported the Loyalist cause and served as allies of the Kingdom of Great Britain; most notably rented auxiliary troops from German states such as the Landgraviate of Hessen-Kassel.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots tended to represent such troops as mercenaries in propaganda against the British Crown.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Even American historians followed suit, in spite of Colonial-era jurists drawing a distinction between auxiliaries and mercenaries, with auxiliaries serving their prince when sent to the aid of another prince, and mercenaries serving a foreign prince as individuals.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] By this distinction the troops which served in the American Revolution were auxiliaries.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Other German individuals came to assist the American revolutionaries, most notably Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben, who served as a general in the Continental Army and is credited with professionalizing that force, but most Germans who served were already colonists.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Von Steuben's native Prussia joined the League of Armed Neutrality, and King Frederick II of Prussia was well appreciated in the United States for his support early in the war.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] He expressed interest in opening trade with the United States and bypassing English ports, and allowed an American agent to buy arms in Prussia.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Frederick predicted American success, and promised to recognize the United States and American diplomats once France did the same.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Prussia also interfered in the recruiting efforts of Russia and neighboring German states when they raised armies to send to the Americas, and Frederick II forbade enlistment for the American war within Prussia.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] All Prussian roads were denied to troops from Anhalt-Zerbst, which delayed reinforcements that Howe had hoped to receive during the winter of 1777–1778.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] However, when the War of the Bavarian Succession (1778–1779) erupted, Frederick II became much more cautious with Prussian/British relations.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] U.S. ships were denied access to Prussian ports, and Frederick refused to officially recognize the United States until they had signed the Treaty of Paris.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Even after the war, Frederick II predicted that the United States was too large to operate as a republic, and that it would soon rejoin the British Empire with representatives in Parliament.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Most Indigenous people rejected pleas that they remain neutral and instead supported the British Crown.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The great majority of the ~200,000 indigenous people east of the Mississippi distrusted the Americans and supported the British cause, hoping to forestall continued expansion of settlement into their territories.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Those tribes closely involved in trade tended to side with the Patriots, although political factors were important as well.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Some tried to remain neutral, seeing little value in joining what they perceived to be a "white man's war", and fearing reprisals from whichever side they opposed.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The British did have other indigenous allies, particularly in the regions of southwest Quebec on the Patriot's frontier.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The British provided arms to Indigenous people who were led by Loyalists in war parties to raid frontier settlements from the Carolinas to New York.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] These war parties killed many settlers on the frontier, especially in western Pennsylvania and New York's Mohawk Valley.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In 1776, Cherokee war parties attacked American settlers all along the southern Quebec frontier of the uplands throughout the Washington District, North Carolina (now Tennessee) and the Kentucky wilderness area.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Chickamauga Cherokee under Tsiyu Gansini (*also* Dragging Canoe) allied themselves closely with the British, and fought on for an additional decade after the Treaty of Paris was signed.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They launched raids with roughly 200 warriors, as seen in the Cherokee–American wars; they could not mobilize enough forces to invade settler areas without the help of allies, most often the Creek.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Joseph Brant (*also* Thayendanegea), from the powerful Mohawk tribe of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy, was the most prominent Indigenous leader against the Patriot forces.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In 1778 and 1780, he led 300 Iroquois warriors and 100 white Loyalists in multiple attacks on small frontier settlements in New York and Pennsylvania, killing many settlers and destroying villages, crops, and food stockpiles.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In 1779, the Continental Army forced the hostile Indigenous people out of upstate New York when Washington sent an army under John Sullivan which destroyed 40 evacuated Iroquois villages in central and western New York.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The Battle of Newtown proved decisive, as the Patriots had an advantage of three-to-one, and it ended significant resistance; there was little combat otherwise.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Facing starvation and homeless for the winter, the Iroquois that allied with the British fled to Canada.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] At the peace conference following the war, the British ceded lands which they did not really control, without consultation with their Indigenous allies that inhabited them.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They transferred control to the United States of all the land south of the Great Lakes east of the Mississippi and north of Florida.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The existence of slavery in the American colonies had attracted criticism from both sides of the Atlantic as many could not reconcile the existence of the institution with the egalitarian ideals espoused by leaders of the Revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The English writer Samuel Johnson wrote "how is it we hear the loudest yelps for liberty among the drivers of the Negroes?" in a text opposing the grievances of the colonists.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Crispus Attucks, of mixed racial heritage, was one of the five people killed in the Boston Massacre in 1770 and is considered the first American casualty for the cause of independence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Free Blacks in the New England Colonies and Middle Colonies in the North as well as Southern Colonies fought on both sides of the War, but the majority fought for the Patriots.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Gary Nash reports that there were about 9,000 Black veteran Patriots, counting the Continental Army and Navy, state militia units, privateers, wagoneers in the Army, servants to officers, and spies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The effects of the war were more dramatic in the South.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Tens of thousands of enslaved persons escaped to British lines throughout the South, causing dramatic losses to slaveholders and disrupting cultivation and harvesting of crops.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] For instance, South Carolina was estimated to have lost about 25,000 enslaved persons to flight, migration, or death which amounted to a third of its enslaved population.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] As noted by the historian Karen Cook Bell, during the Revolutionary War roughly one-third of all the escaped enslaved were women, even though prior to 1775 nearly 87% had been men.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] During the war, British commanders attempted to weaken the Patriots by issuing proclamations of freedom to their enslaved.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] In the November 1775 document known as Dunmore's Proclamation Virginia royal governor, Lord Dunmore recruited Black men for British military service with the promise of freedom, protection for their families, and land grants.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Hundreds of Black men responded and were formed into the Royal Ethiopian Regiment.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Colonists, primarily Southern Patriots, were deeply angered by Dunmore's proclamation, which spread through all of the Thirteen Colonies and threatened to upturn the existing American racial hierarchy; it also played a major role in Southern support for American independence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Accusations that the British were encouraging slave rebellions were prominent features of Patriot propaganda, with Jefferson even accusing George III in the 27 colonial grievances of having "excited domestic Insurrections among us".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] The 1779 Philipsburg Proclamation expanded the promise of freedom for Black men who enlisted in the British military to all the colonies in rebellion.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] At the conclusion of the war, British forces gave transportation to 10,000 of the formerly enslaved when they evacuated Savannah and Charles Town, carrying through on their promise.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] They evacuated and resettled more than 3,000 Black Loyalists from New York to Nova Scotia, Upper Canada, and Lower Canada.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Others sailed with the British to England or were resettled as freedmen in the West Indies of the Caribbean.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] But the enslaved carried to the Caribbean under control of Loyalist masters generally remained enslaved until the British abolition of slavery in its colonies in 1833–1838.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] More than 1,200 of the Black Loyalists of Nova Scotia later resettled in the British colony of Sierra Leone in Africa, where they became leaders of the Krio ethnic group of Freetown and the later national government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Many of their descendants still live in Sierra Leone, as well as other African countries.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Despite the turmoil of the period, African-Americans contributed to the foundation of an American national identity during the Revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p02] Phyllis Wheatley, an African American poet, popularized the image of Columbia to represent America.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] After the Revolution, genuinely democratic politics became possible in the former American colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The rights of the people were incorporated into state constitutions.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Concepts of liberty, consent of the governed, individual rights, equality and due process under the law, and intolerance of corruption became incorporated as core values of liberal republicanism.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The new United States government was empowered to undertake its own project of territorial expansion and settler colonialism.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The greatest challenge to the old order in Europe was the challenge to inherited political power and the democratic idea that government rests on the consent of the governed.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Losing the war and the Thirteen Colonies was a shock to Britain.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The war revealed the limitations of Britain's fiscal-military state when they discovered that they suddenly faced powerful enemies with no allies, and they were dependent on extended and vulnerable transatlantic lines of communication.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The defeat heightened dissension and escalated political antagonism to the king's ministers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The king went so far as to draft letters of abdication, although they were never delivered.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Inside Parliament, the primary concern changed from fears of an over-mighty monarch to the issues of representation, parliamentary reform, and government retrenchment.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Unable to accept loss of the war and the colonies as possibly due to anything else but widespread institutional corruption, reformers sought to root it out, and the result was a crisis from 1776 to 1783.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The crisis ended after 1784 confidence in the British constitution was restored during the administration of Prime Minister William Pitt.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution ended an age—an age of monarchy.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] And, it began a new age—an age of freedom.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] As a result of the growing wave started by the Revolution, there are now more people around the world living in freedom than ever before, both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of the world's population.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Interpretations vary concerning the effect of the Revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Historians such as Bernard Bailyn, Gordon Wood, and Edmund Morgan view it as a unique and radical event which produced deep changes and had a profound effect on world affairs, such as an increasing belief in the principles of the Enlightenment.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] These were demonstrated by a leadership and government that espoused protection of natural rights, and a system of laws chosen by the people.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] John Murrin, by contrast, argues that the definition of "the people" at that time was mostly restricted to free men who passed a property qualification.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The first shot of the American Revolution at the Battle of Lexington and Concord is referred to as the "shot heard 'round the world".
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution was the first of the Atlantic Revolutions: followed most notably by the French Revolution, the Haitian Revolution, and the Latin American wars of independence.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Aftershocks contributed to rebellions in Ireland, the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, and the Netherlands.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Constitution, drafted shortly after independence, remains the world's oldest written constitution, and has been emulated by other countries, in some cases verbatim.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Some historians and scholars argue that the subsequent wave of independence and revolutionary movements has contributed to the continued expansion of democratic government; 144 countries, representing two-third of the world's population, are full or partially democracies of some form.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution had a strong, immediate influence in Great Britain, Ireland, the Netherlands, and France.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Many British and Irish Whigs in Parliament spoke glowingly in favor of the American cause.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] In Ireland, the Protestant minority who controlled Ireland demanded self-rule.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Under the leadership of Henry Grattan, the Irish Patriot Party forced the reversal of mercantilist prohibitions against trade with other British colonies.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The King and his cabinet in London could not risk another rebellion, and so made a series of concessions to the Patriot faction in Dublin.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Armed volunteer units of the *Protestant Ascendancy* were set up ostensibly to protect against an invasion from France.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] As had been in colonial America, so too in Ireland now the King no longer had a monopoly of lethal force.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] By 1798, the Irish were ready for a republican uprising.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] For many Europeans, such as the Marquis de Lafayette, who later were active during the era of the French Revolution, the American case along with the Dutch Revolt (end of the 16th century) and the 17th century English Civil War, was among the examples of overthrowing an old regime.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The American Declaration of Independence influenced the French Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen of 1789.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The spirit of the Declaration of Independence led to laws ending slavery in all the Northern states and the Northwest Territory, with New Jersey the last in 1804.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] States such as New Jersey and New York adopted gradual emancipation, which kept some people as slaves for more than two decades longer.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] During the revolution, the contradiction between the Patriots' professed ideals of liberty and the institution of slavery generated increased scrutiny of the latter.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] As early as 1764, the Boston Patriot leader James Otis, Jr. declared that all men, "white or black", were "by the law of nature" born free.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Anti-slavery calls became more common in the early 1770s.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] In 1773, Benjamin Rush, the future signer of the Declaration of Independence, called on "advocates for American liberty" to oppose slavery.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Slavery became an issue that had to be addressed.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] In the late 1760s and early 1770s, several colonies, including Massachusetts and Virginia, attempted to restrict the slave trade, but were prevented from doing so by royally appointed governors.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] In 1774, as part of a broader non-importation movement aimed at Britain, the Continental Congress called on all the colonies to ban the importation of enslaved people, and the colonies passed acts doing so.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] In the first two decades after the American Revolution, state legislatures and individuals took actions to free the enslaved, in part based on Revolutionary ideals.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Northern states passed new constitutions that contained language about equal rights or specifically abolished slavery; some states, such as New York and New Jersey, where slavery was more widespread, passed laws by the end of the 18th century to abolish slavery by a gradual method.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] By 1804, all the northern states had passed laws outlawing slavery, either immediately or over time.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] However, enslavers could grant freedom to individuals they enslaved.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Numerous slaveholders who freed their enslaved cited Revolutionary ideals in their documents; others freed their enslaved as a reward for service.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Records also suggest that some slaveholders were freeing their own mixed-race children, born to enslaved mothers.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The number of free Blacks as a proportion of the Black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Nevertheless, slavery continued in the South, where it was protected as a "peculiar institution", setting the stage for future sectional conflict between North and South over the issue.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Thousands of free Blacks in the northern states fought in the state militias and Continental Army.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] In the south, both sides offered freedom to slaves who would perform military service.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Roughly 20,000 enslaved persons fought in the American Revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] While women were entering a period in which they found themselves gaining more identity within society, it was clear that they were still very much considered under men as their role in society remained being a good wife and mother.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Having a woman who was dressed well for her role as a good wife and mother as well as fitting the social role, was a symbol of not only status, but a family devoted to the republic.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] As they continued to nurture social and political partnerships, their role in enabling the success of the revolution emphasized their changing role in society – leading to the post-revolutionary reconstruction of gender ideology.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] In addition, the democratic ideals of the Revolution inspired changes in the roles of women.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Patriot women married to Loyalists who left the state could get a divorce and obtain control of the ex-husband's property.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] As discussions rose regarding the rights of man post Revolutionary war, women began pushing a debate for the rights of women as well.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Mary Wollstonecraft pioneered the discussion regarding women's rights, and push those like Abigail Adams to begin expressing the desire to want a larger place in society.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Wollstonecraft was an English writer, philosopher, and advocate for women's rights, and would publish the *Vindication of the Rights of Woman* (1792) – challenging the idea that rights should only be granted to men.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Her radical ideas would give ground to the conversation in allowing women to be bearers of rights alongside men – that while the rights of man were taking on a new meaning post-revolutionary America, it was time for the rights of women too.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Inspired by the radical feminism in her work, women in the early republic would change their views on marriage, education, participation in public life, and autonomy – pushing them to lay the groundwork for the later women's suffrage movement, education opportunities, property rights, and more.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] However, this new sense of independence and dignity did not come with ease, as a gender hierarchy would continue to bind what it meant for women to have rights during the post-revolutionary era.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Women in the early republic had many limitations – they could not vote, hold political office, earn fair wages, lacked opportunities for higher education and certain professions, and most importantly, own property independently of their husbands.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] In addition, they held little legal powers in subjects such as divorce, property rights, and child custody.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] A central legal concept that reinforced these restrictions was *coverture*, a central legal doctrine that limited women's lives in all aspects – making a woman's legal identity a part of their husband's.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The early national period of America would continue to struggle with the concept of rights and equality.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Tens of thousands of Loyalists left the United States following the war; Philip Ranlet estimates 20,000, while Maya Jasanoff estimates as many as 70,000.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Some migrated to Britain, but the great majority received land and subsidies for resettlement in British colonies in North America, especially Quebec (concentrating in the Eastern Townships), Prince Edward Island, and Nova Scotia.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Britain created the colonies of Upper Canada (Ontario) and New Brunswick expressly for their benefit, and the Crown awarded land to Loyalists as compensation for losses in the United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Nevertheless, approximately eighty-five percent of the Loyalists stayed in the United States as American citizens, and some of the exiles later returned to the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Patrick Henry spoke of the issue of allowing Loyalists to return as such: "Shall we, who have laid the proud British lion at our feet, be frightened of its whelps?" His actions helped secure return of the Loyalists to American soil.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution has a central place in the American memory as the story of the nation's founding.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] It is covered in the schools, memorialized by two national holidays, Washington's Birthday in February and Independence Day in July, and commemorated in innumerable monuments.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] George Washington's estate at Mount Vernon was one of the first national pilgrimages for tourists and attracted 10,000 visitors a year by the 1850s.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution became a matter of contention in the 1850s in the debates leading to the American Civil War (1861–1865), as spokesmen of both the Northern United States and the Southern United States claimed that their region was the true custodian of the legacy of 1776.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The United States Bicentennial in 1976 came a year after the American withdrawal from the Vietnam War, and speakers stressed the themes of renewal and rebirth based on a restoration of traditional values.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] Today, more than 100 battlefields and historic sites of the American Revolution are protected and maintained by the government.
[src:alfred-f-young/american-revolution-p03] The National Park Service alone manages and maintains more than 50 battlefield parks and many other sites such as Independence Hall that are related to the Revolution.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] A **Bachelor of Arts** (abbreviated **BA** or **AB**; from the Latin **baccalaureus artium**, **baccalaureus in artibus**, or **artium baccalaureus**) is the holder of a bachelor's degree awarded for an undergraduate program in the liberal arts, or, in some cases, other disciplines.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] A Bachelor of Arts degree course is generally completed in three or four years, depending on the country and institution.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree is an undergraduate postsecondary degree that puts a focus on liberal arts and studies.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In comparison, a Bachelor of Science (BS or BSc) has a greater focus on science, math, and engineering.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The Bachelor of Arts degree is a type of baccalaureate degree.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] A Bachelor of Arts degree is usually completed in four years: that is, it requires four years of full-time coursework during term time.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] However, just as with other degrees, some may require a longer time period.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] This is due to factors such as the student's ability, motivation, and access to financial assistance to earn the degree.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Just like other baccalaureate degrees, a Bachelor of Arts is historically offered only at public and private universities and colleges.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] A Bachelor of Arts, just like other bachelor's degrees, is an admission requirement for graduate and professional school.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Beginning in the 1990s, junior colleges started to confer their own baccalaureate degrees.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In addition to the standard BA degrees, there are career-specific Bachelors of Arts degree, including Bachelor of Arts in Functional English, Bachelor of Arts in Administration, Bachelor of Arts in Interdisciplinary Studies, and Regents Bachelor of Arts.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The Bachelor of Arts degree has been prominent in academics for centuries.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] It influenced universities to begin focusing on broad topics such as algebra, psychology, biology, art, history, and philosophy.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] This aspect of the BA degree has been consistent in its history.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The Bachelor of Arts degree was formed out of the study of liberal arts.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] *Liberal art* is a term that was applied to the study of many branches of learning such as grammar, logic, rhetoric, arithmetic, geometry, astronomy, and music.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The study of liberal arts started during the Middle Ages.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] During the Renaissance, the term *liberal* *art* was meant to describe general studies more broadly.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] This definition of liberal studies remains to this day.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In Japan and the United States, Bachelor of Arts degrees were historically given only by public or private institutions and colleges.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In Germany, university-level education usually happens in either a *Universität* (plural: *Universitäten*) or a *Fachhochschule* (plural: *Fachhochschulen*); both can be referred to as a *Hochschule*, which is the generic term in Germany for all institutions awarding academic degrees.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] *Fachhochschule* is often translated as "University of Applied Sciences".
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] *Universitäten* place greater emphasis on fundamental science and background in theory, while *Fachhochschulen* are generally designed with a focus on teaching professional skills.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Degrees earned at *Universitäten* and *Fachhochschulen* are legally equivalent.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In Germany, the BA course normally lasts between three and three and a half years—six or seven semesters—and the degree is awarded after the student earns between 180 and 210 ECTS.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In the Netherlands, the BA and Master of Arts (MA) degrees were introduced in 2002.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Until then, a single program led to the *doctorandus* degree (abbreviated drs.), which comprised the same course load as the bachelor's and master's programs combined.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The title *doctorandus* was used in almost all fields of study; other titles were used for legal studies (*meester*, Dutch for master, abbreviated *Mr.*) and engineering (*ingenieur*, abbreviated Ir. for academic masters level or ING. for higher vocational bachelor's level).
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Those who had already started the *doctorandus* program could, on completing it, opt for the *doctorandus* degree (entitling them to use "drs." in front of their name) or could use the master's degree (post-nominal letters) in accordance with the new standard.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] When attaining a master level/graduate degree, it is still customary to use either drs. pre-nominally or MA/MSc post-nominally at the discretion of the holder.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In the United Kingdom (excluding Scotland) and Ireland, the first degree course normally lasts three years, but nomenclature varies: 19th-century and later universities usually distinguish between arts and sciences subjects by awarding either a BA or BSc degree.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Some new plate glass universities established in the 1960s, such as York and Lancaster, originally followed the practice of Oxford and Cambridge by awarding BAs in all subjects, but have since changed to awarding BSc degrees in science subjects.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] At Oxford, Cambridge, and Dublin the degree of MA can be claimed, usually twenty-one terms after matriculation, without any further study.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] For many centuries, the bachelor's degree was an intermediate step and was awarded for much of the work carried out in later times at secondary schools.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The names of the final secondary school exams in France and Spain (and of the International Baccalaureate) come from this: *le Baccalauréat* and *el Bachillerato*, respectively.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The ancient universities of Scotland award a Master of Arts degree to humanities or arts graduates, but a BSc to science graduates.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] This course takes four years for an honours degree and three for an ordinary.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In Scotland, one can opt to take an ordinary degree, which ranks below a third class honours degree (for example, BA with distinction, merit or pass).
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] A Bachelor of Arts is entitled to the post-nominal letters BA for an ordinary or pass degree and BA (Hons) for an honours degree.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The academic dress worn by honours and non-honours graduates is identical.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] An honours degree is always awarded in one of four classes, depending upon the marks gained in the final assessments and examinations.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The top students are awarded a first-class degree, followed by an upper second-class degree (usually referred to as a 2:1), a lower second-class degree (usually referred to as a 2:2), and those who pass with the lowest marks gain a third-class degree.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] An ordinary, pass or unclassified degree (which does not give the graduate the right to add "Hons") may be awarded if a student has completed (i) followed a non-honours program, or (b) attempted an honours course but marginally failed to achieve third-class standard.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Education in Canada is controlled by the provinces and can be very different depending on the province.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] While all Canadian universities offer four-year degrees, it is not uncommon, depending on the province and the university for a three-year general degree to also be offered as an option.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In many universities and colleges, Bachelor of Arts degrees are differentiated either as BA or as honours BA degrees.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Honours programs require more education than non-honours programs, typically a specialization beyond the requirements of a BA, and can sometimes be used as a gateway to a PhD program, bypassing a master's degree.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In Québec, BA degrees generally last three years, because the fourth year is replaced by CEGEP education (which fills the gap between Secondary V, the last year of high school, and the first year of university).
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] However, four-year programs exist for students having completed 12 (instead of 13) years of education prior to being admitted to university.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Along with the Bachelor of Science (BS), the Bachelor of Arts (BA) is the most commonly granted degree in the United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] A BA degree is usually earned after the completion of four years of undergraduate college level study.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Some universities in the United States abbreviate the degree as "AB" or "A.B.", derived from the Latin title *Artium Baccalaureatus*.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] AB degrees are particularly associated with Ivy League institutions and other universities with historical ties to Latin academic traditions—such as Harvard, Princeton, Brown, the University of Chicago, and Bryn Mawr College.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] These schools use the AB (or A.B.) designation to distinguish their degree from the more common Bachelor of Arts (BA).
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The use of Latin terminology underscores their heritage and the prestige of their academic programs, where the study of Greek and Latin had traditionally been a fundamental component of the undergraduate curriculum at these institutions.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] The College of Charleston also offers the A.B. degree as an option with the requirement that students demonstrate proficiency in either Latin or Greek.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In colleges and universities in Australia, Nepal, New Zealand, India and South Africa, the BA degree can be taken over three years of full-time study.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] Students must pursue at least one major area of study and units from that subject are usually studied in each year, though sometimes students may choose to complete upper-level classes in the same year and as a result, can leave space for elective subjects from a different field.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] At some universities, students may choose to pursue a second major; alternatively, the remainder of the degree is taken up with a minor area of study (in the first two years) and other individual or stream-based subjects.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] In Pakistan the Bachelor of Arts (BA) program used to be regular 2-year degree program in which students were offered with a combination of any two of areas from the available electives: Business, Journalism, Psychology, Computer Science and Education.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] However, now all bachelor's degree courses are 4-year program.
[src:alfred-f-young/bachelor-of-arts] 2 years degree is now called associate degree.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] The history of Beacon Press actually begins in 1825, the year the American Unitarian Association (AUA) was formed.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] This liberal religious movement had the enlightened notion to publish and distribute books and tracts that would spread the word of their beliefs not only about theology but also about society and justice.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] In the Press of the American Unitarian Association (as Beacon was called then) purchased and published works that were largely religious in nature and "conservative Unitarian" in viewpoint (far more progressive, nonetheless, than many other denominations).
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] The authors were often Unitarian ministers—dead or alive, American or British, mostly Caucasian, and far more male than female.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Many of the books were collections of sermons, lectures, and letters, balanced by volumes of devotion, hymns, and morally uplifting tales.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] In the early 1900s Samuel Eliot broadened the mission of the press by publishing books dealing with ethical, sociological, philanthropic, and similar subjects, as well as those of a more strictly religious character....
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] In 1949, Beacon published *American Freedom and Catholic Power*, an anti-Catholic tome written by socialist and secular humanist Paul Blanshard, who was the assistant editor for The Nation.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Beacon would go on to publish several other books by Blanshard critical of Catholicism over the next few decades.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Under director Gobin Stair (1962–75), new authors included James Baldwin, Kenneth Clark, André Gorz, Herbert Marcuse, Jürgen Habermas, Howard Zinn, Ben Bagdikian, Mary Daly, and Jean Baker Miller.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Wendy Strothman became Beacon's director in 1983; she set up the organization's first advisory board, a group of scholars and publishing professionals who advised on book choices and direction.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] She turned a budget deficit into a surplus.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] In 1995, her last year at Beacon, Strothman summarized the Press's mission: "We at Beacon publish the books we choose because they share a moral vision and a sense that greater understanding can influence the course of events.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] They are books we believe in." Strothman was replaced by Helene Atwan in 1995.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] In 1971, it published the "Senator Gravel edition" of *The Pentagon Papers* for the first time in book form, when no other publisher was willing to risk publishing such controversial material.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Robert West, then-president of the Unitarian Universalist Association, approved the decision to publish *The Pentagon Papers*, which West claims resulted in two-and-a-half years of harassment and intimidation by the Nixon administration.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] United States*, the Supreme Court decided that the Constitution's "Speech or Debate Clause" protected Gravel and some acts of his aide, but not Beacon Press.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Beacon Press is a member of the Association of University Presses.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Beacon Press publishes non-fiction, fiction, and poetry titles.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Some of Beacon's best-known titles are listed below.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] The following is a list of some of the principal series; it is not comprehensive.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] In 2009, Beacon Press announced a new partnership with the Estate of Martin Luther King Jr. for a new book series publishing program, "The King Legacy." As part of the program, Beacon is printing new editions of previously published King titles and compiling Dr.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] King's writings, sermons, orations, lectures, and prayers into entirely new editions, including new introductions by leading scholars.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] Beacon Press launched its blog, *Beacon Broadside*, in late September 2007.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] In 1992, Beacon won a New England Book Award for publishing.
[src:alfred-f-young/beacon-press] In 1993, Beacon was voted "Trade Publisher of the Year" by the Literary Market Place.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The English dramatist Philip Massinger used the phrase "black list" in his 1639 tragedy *The Unnatural Combat*.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] After the restoration of the English monarchy brought Charles II of England to the throne in 1660, a list of regicides named those to be punished for the execution of his father.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The state papers of Charles II say "If any innocent soul be found in this black list, let him not be offended at me, but consider whether some mistaken principle or interest may not have misled him to vote".
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] In a 1676 history of the events leading up to the Restoration, James Heath (a supporter of Charles II) alleged that Parliament had passed an Act requiring the sale of estates, "And into this black list the Earl of Derby was now put, and other unfortunate Royalists".
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Edward Gibbon wrote in *The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* (1776) of Andronicus that "His memory was stored with a black list of the enemies and rivals, who had traduced his merit, opposed his greatness, or insulted his misfortunes".
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The first published reference to blacklisting of an employee dates from 1774.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] This became a significant employment issue in American mining towns and company towns, where blacklisting could mean a complete loss of livelihood for workers who went on strike.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Though the USA National Labor Relations Act of 1935 outlawed punitive blacklists against employees who supported trade unions or criticised their employers, the practice continued in common use in the USA.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The Taft-Hartley Act of 1947 made amendments which sustained blacklisting by affirming the right of employers to be anti-union, and by requiring trade union leaders to make loyalty oaths which had the same effect as the Hollywood blacklist.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Since then, lawsuits for unfair dismissal have led to blacklisting being covert or informal, but it remains common.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] In 1981, following the PATCO workers' refusal to return to work, the Reagan administration fired the 11,345 striking air traffic controllers who had ignored the order, and banned them from federal service for life.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The Hollywood blacklist was an entertainment industry blacklist instituted in 1947 to block screenwriters and other Hollywood professionals who were purported to have Communist sympathies from obtaining employment.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] It started by listing 151 entertainment industry professionals and lasted until 1960 when it was effectively broken by the acknowledgement that blacklisted professionals had been working under assumed names for many years.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] During World War I, the British government adopted a "blacklist" based on an Order in Council of 23 December 1915, prohibiting British subjects from trade with specified firms and individuals in neutral countries; the lists were published in the *London Gazette*.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] In the summer of 1940, the SS printed a secret list called *Sonderfahndungsliste G.B.* ("Special Search List Great Britain") as part of Nazi Germany's preparations for invasion code-named Operation Sea Lion.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] When this booklet was found after the war, it was commonly called the Black Book and described as a blacklist.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] In 1907, the Transvaal Medical Union in South Africa blacklisted patients if they could not pay cash in advance.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] There was a physical list kept by the community of physicians.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] After the 2004 Venezuelan recall referendum, ruling party deputy Luis Tascón published on his website a database of more than 2,400,000 Venezuelans who had signed the petition to recall President Hugo Chávez, together with their national identity card numbers (*cédula*).
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The list "made sectarianism official", and Venezuelans who signed against Chávez were denied jobs, benefits, and documents, and often subjected to harassment.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Once the list was posted, Chávez, on a *Venezolana de Televisión* broadcast, encouraged use of the website to "verify illicit use of national identity cards".
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Roger Capella, Minister of Health declared that "those who signed against President Chávez would be fired because they are committing an act of terrorism".
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] There was a public outcry, in particular by the organization Súmate, and because of reports that people who worked for the government were fired, denied work, or denied issuance of official documents because of their appearance on the list.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Following the October 7 attacks, singers who posted their support for Israel on social media reportedly were blacklisted at venues where they typically performed.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] A professional gamer was barred from a competition for similar reasons.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] In Chicago, Jewish therapists who said they would treat a Zionist patient were added to a blacklist.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] British sociologist David Hirsh noted that Zionist academics “have not been able to publish, people were not able to do the things that you need to do in order to build a career in academia”.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] After having a scheduled lecture canceled, historian and sociologist Izabella Tabarovsky said that "as a former Soviet citizen she was 'deeply familiar' with this kind of silencing".
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] In computing, a blacklist is an access control system that denies entry to a specific list (or a defined range) of users, programs, or network addresses.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] In 2018, a medical journal commentary regarding predatory publishing was published, arguing that *whitelist*, *blacklist*, among other terms, reinforce existing racial biases and should be avoided in medical literature.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The commentary gained public attention in Summer 2020 following the George Floyd protests in the United States wherein a black man died in the custody of Minneapolis police officers, sparking protests against police brutality.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The commentary cites examples of the use of *black* as a shorthand for disreputable sources and other negative judgements, and *white* for trustworthiness and safety.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] The article also notes the origins of *blacklist* as a label for censure and punishment of workers involved in labor unions, and that early use of the term coincides with the rise of slavery in the Americas, but does not claim its etymology as referring directly to skin color.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Conflict around this issue often emerges in computing industries where *whitelist* and *blacklist* are prevalent (e.g.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Some companies, open-source communities, and software developers have chosen to deprecate use of *whitelist* and *blacklist* in favor of names which describe the purpose of those lists less ambiguously and are unlikely to come across to a reader as insensitive such as *allow list* and *deny list*.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] An IETF draft technical proposal has been underway since 2018 presenting arguments for avoiding potentially exclusionary language in technical documentation and a standardized set of recommendations for their replacement.
[src:alfred-f-young/blacklisting] Before garnering wider public attention in 2020, similarly motivated changes have also been enacted in years prior to replace terminology such as *master/slave* with alternatives due to concerns over their potential role in workplace discrimination.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The C-SPAN network includes the television channels C-SPAN, focusing on the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] House of Representatives; **C-SPAN2**, focusing on the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Senate; and **C-SPAN3**, airing other government hearings and related programming; the radio station WCSP-FM; and a group of websites which provide streaming media and program archives.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN's television channels are available to approximately 100 million cable and satellite households within the United States.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] WCSP-FM is broadcast on FM radio in Washington, D.C., and is available throughout the U.S. on SiriusXM via Internet streaming, TuneIn, and globally through iOS and Android apps.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The network televises U.S. political events, particularly live and "gavel-to-gavel" coverage of the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Congress, as well as other major events worldwide.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Coverage of political and policy events is unmoderated, providing the audience with unfiltered information about politics and government.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Non-political coverage includes historical programming, programs dedicated to non-fiction books, and interview programs with noteworthy individuals associated with public policy.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Brian Lamb, C-SPAN's chairman and former chief executive officer, conceived C-SPAN in 1975 while working as the Washington, D.C., bureau chief of *Cablevision*.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Cable television was a rapidly growing industry, and Lamb envisioned a non-profit network, financed by the cable industry, that televised Congressional sessions, public affairs events, and policy discussions.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Bob Rosencrans, providing $25,000 of initial funding in 1979, and John D.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Evans, providing wiring and access to the headend needed for the distribution of the C-SPAN signal, were among those who helped Lamb launch the network.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] At meetings with House of Representatives leadership, Lamb and Rosencrans promised that the network would be non-political, which helped override broadcast and local network resistance.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN was launched on March 19, 1979, for the first televised session made available by the House of Representatives, beginning with a speech by then-Tennessee representative and later senator, Vice President, and presidential candidate Al Gore.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Upon its debut, only 3.5 million homes were wired for C-SPAN, and the network had just three employees.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] For the first few years C-SPAN leased satellite time from the USA Network and had approximately 9 hours of daily programming.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] On February 1, 1982, C-SPAN launched its own transponder and expanded programming to 16 hours a day; the arrangement with the USA Network was discontinued two months later.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN began full-time operations on September 13, 1982.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN2 was launched on June 2, 1986, to cover Senate proceedings, and began full-time operations on January 5, 1987.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The Senate had debated allowing television coverage for over two years, with Majority Leader Howard Baker introducing the first, failed, resolution to allow cameras onto the floor and Senator William L.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Armstrong finally succeeding in televising Senate proceedings.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 1992, Congress passed must-carry regulations, which required cable carriers to allocate spectrum to local broadcasters.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] This affected the availability of C-SPAN, especially C-SPAN2, in some areas as some providers chose to discontinue carriage of the channel altogether.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Between 1993 and 1994, cable systems in 95 U.S. cities dropped or reduced broadcasts of C-SPAN and C-SPAN2.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Viewers protested these decisions, and some communities, such as Eugene, Oregon and Alexandria, Virginia, were successful in restoring C-SPAN availability.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN availability was broadly restored when technological improvements expanded channel capacity and allowed for both mandatory stations and the C-SPAN networks to be broadcast.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN3, began full-time operations on January 22, 2001.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] It airs public policy and government-related events on weekdays, historical programming on weeknights and weekends, and sometimes serves as an overflow channel for live programming conflicts on C-SPAN and C-SPAN2.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN3 is the successor of a digital channel called C-SPAN Extra, which was launched in the Washington, D.C., area in 1997, and televised live and recorded political events on weekdays.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN Radio also began operations in 1997, covering similar events as the television networks and often simulcasting their programming.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2010, C-SPAN began a transition to high definition telecasts, planned to take place over an 18-month period.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The network provided C-SPAN and C-SPAN2 in high definition on June 1, 2010, and C-SPAN3 in July 2010.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2012, Lamb became executive chair of C-SPAN; Susan Swain and Robert Kennedy succeeded him as co-chief executive officers (CEO).
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Swain and Kennedy were succeeded as CEO by Sam Feist, head of CNN's Washington D.C. news bureau, in 2024.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Lamb retired in 2024 and was succeeded as chair by Patrick Esser.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In January 1997, C-SPAN began real-time streaming of C-SPAN and C-SPAN2 on its website.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] To cover the Democratic and Republican conventions and the presidential debates of 2008, C-SPAN created two standalone websites: the Convention Hub and the Debate Hub.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-span.org features further live programming such as committee hearings and speeches that are broadcast later in the day, after the House and Senate have left.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] On January 12, 2017, the online feed for C-SPAN1 was interrupted and replaced by a feed from the Russian television network RT America for approximately 10 minutes.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN broadcasts video feed, but does not control the placement or number of cameras on the House and Senate floor.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Arguments over C-SPAN's camera in the House and Senate began as early as 1984, with a fight between Democrats and Republicans over camera angles.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] At the time C-SPAN only broadcast a shot of the person speaking.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The Conservative Opportunity Society, led by Newt Gingrich, took advantage of this by delivering speeches to an empty chamber, at times referring to Democrats who were not actually there.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Speaker Tip O'Neill, annoyed by the speeches, ordered the camera to display a wide-shot of the empty chamber without alerting the Republicans.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The incident turned into a widely publicized argument between Gingrich and O'Neill.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] After the 1984 incident, the House allowed both wide-angle shots and close-ups of the speaker until 1994, when they reverted to just close-up shots in an effort to make the House look "more dignified." The Senate, which had allowed cameras since 1987, had always only allowed close-ups.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 1994, C-SPAN requested increased camera access from both the Senate and the House of Representatives, and for permission to bring their own cameras.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] They asked permission to pan for wide reaction shots, and install cameras for House-Senate conference committees and off-floor interviews, among other things.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] They also asked permission to have C-SPAN employees man the cameras instead of government employees.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Speaker Dennis Hastert rejected similar requests in 1999, as well as incoming Speaker Nancy Pelosi in 2006.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] A December 2009 request to film healthcare negotiations was similarly denied.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2011, C-SPAN again requested to bring cameras onto the House floor.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] On June 22 and 23, 2016, C-SPAN took video footage of the House floor from individual House representatives via streaming services Periscope and Facebook Live during a sit-in by House Democrats asking for a vote on gun control measures after the Orlando nightclub shooting.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The sit-in was out of formal session and while the House was in official recess, so the existing House cameras could not be used to cover the event.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] These live streams violated House rules on use of personal devices on the floor, which C-SPAN noted through on-air disclaimers.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In January 2023, C-SPAN gained widespread attention for its broadcast of the Speaker of the House vote.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] As the House was not in session, C-SPAN had been given permission for its cameras to roam the House floor, and capture new angles in addition to the often-permitted wide-angle and speaker close-up.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] After Kevin McCarthy was confirmed as Speaker, camera permissions reverted to what had previously been permitted.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN has requested televised camera access for arguments before the United States Supreme Court.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Its requests have been denied or ignored by the court.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The C-SPAN network's core programming is live coverage of the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] House and Senate, with the C-SPAN channel emphasizing the United States House of Representatives.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Between 1979 and May 2011, the network televised more than 24,246 hours of floor action.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN2, the first of the C-SPAN sister networks, provides uninterrupted live coverage of the United States Senate.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] With coverage of the House and Senate, viewers can track legislation as it moves through both bodies of Congress.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Important debates in Congress that C-SPAN has covered live include the Persian Gulf conflict during 1991, and the House impeachment vote and Senate trial of President Bill Clinton in 1998 and 1999 as well as the impeachment proceedings of President Trump in 2019 and 2020.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] When the House or Senate are not in session, C-SPAN channels broadcast other public affairs programming and recordings of previous events.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The public affairs coverage on the C-SPAN networks other than the House and Senate floor debates is wide-ranging.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN is considered a useful source of information for journalists, lobbyists, educators and government officials as well as casual viewers interested in politics, due to its unedited coverage of political events.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN has been described by media observers as a "window into the world of Washington politics" and it characterizes its own mission as being "to provide public access to the political process".
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The networks cover U.S. political campaigns, including the Republican, Democratic, and Libertarian presidential nominating conventions in their entirety.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Coverage of presidential campaign events are provided during the duration of the campaign, both by a weekly television program, *Campaign*, and at its dedicated campaign website.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] All three channels televise events such as congressional hearings, White House press briefings and presidential speeches, as well as other government meetings including Federal Communications Commission hearings and Pentagon press conferences.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Other U.S. political coverage includes State of the Union speeches, and presidential press conferences.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] According to the results of a survey after the 1992 presidential election, 85% of C-SPAN viewers voted in that election.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The results of a similar survey in 2013 found that 89% of C-SPAN viewers voted in the 2012 presidential election.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In addition to this political coverage, the network broadcasts press conferences and meetings of various news media and nonprofit organizations, including those at the National Press Club, public policy seminars and the White House Correspondents' Dinner.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] While C-SPAN does not have video access to the Supreme Court, the network has used the Court's audio recordings accompanied by still photographs of the justices and lawyers to cover the Court in session on significant cases, and has covered individual Supreme Court justices' speaking engagements.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Occasionally, proceedings of the Parliament of Australia, Parliament of Canada, Parliament of the United Kingdom (usually Prime Minister's Questions and the State Opening of Parliament) and other governments are shown on C-SPAN when they discuss matters of importance to viewers in the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Similarly, the networks will sometimes broadcast news reports from around the world when major events occur – for instance, C-SPAN broadcast CBC Television coverage of the September 11 attacks.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN also covers lying in state in the Capitol Rotunda and funerals of former presidents and other notable individuals.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2005, C-SPAN covered Hurricane Katrina through NBC affiliate WDSU in New Orleans, as well as coverage of Hurricane Ike via CBS affiliate KHOU in Houston.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN also carries CBC coverage during events that affect Canadians, such as the Canadian federal elections, the death and state funeral of Pierre Trudeau, and the 2003 North America blackout.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] During early 2011, C-SPAN carried broadcasts by Al Jazeera to cover the events in Egypt, Tunisia, and other Arab nations.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Additionally, C-SPAN simulcasts NASA Space Shuttle mission launches and landings live, using video footage and audio sourced from NASA TV.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] With its public affairs programming, C-SPAN intends to offer different viewpoints by allowing time for multiple opinions to be discussed on a given topic.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] When Lipstadt ended media access to her speech, C-SPAN canceled coverage of both.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The network strives for neutrality and a lack of bias; in all programming when on-camera hosts are present their role is simply to facilitate and explain proceedings to the viewer.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Due to this policy, C-SPAN hosts do not state their names on television.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN covers floor proceedings of the House of Representatives, while C-SPAN 2 covers floor proceedings of the Senate.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Although many hours of programming on C-SPAN are dedicated to coverage of the House, the network's daily programming begins with the political phone-in and interview program *Washington Journal* from 7:00 to 10:00 a.m.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] *Washington Journal* premiered on January 4, 1995, and has been broadcast every morning since then, with guests including elected officials, government administrators, and journalists.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The program covers current events, with guests answering questions on topics presented by the hosts, as well as questions from members of the general public.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] On weeknights C-SPAN2 dedicates its schedule to *Politics and Public Policy Today* (9:00 p.m. – midnight for the East Coast primetime, replayed immediately for the West Coast primetime), which is a block of recordings of the day's noteworthy events in rapid succession.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] On the weekend schedule, C-SPAN's main program is *Q&A*, a Sunday evening interview program hosted by Peter Slen, with guests including journalists, politicians, authors, and other public figures.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN2 dedicates its Sunday schedule to *Book TV*, which is programming about non-fiction books, book events, and authors.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] *Book TV* was launched in September 1998.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] *Booknotes* was originally broadcast from 1989 to 2004, as a one-hour one-on-one interview of a non-fiction author.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Repeats of the interviews remain a regular part of the *Book TV* schedule with the title *Encore Booknotes*.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Other *Book TV* programs feature political and historical books and biographies of public figures.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] These include *In Depth*, a live, monthly, three-hour interview with a single author, and *After Words*, an author interview program featuring guest hosts interviewing authors on topics with which both are familiar.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] *After Words* was developed as a new type of author interview program after the end of production of *Booknotes*.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Weekend programming on *Book TV* also includes coverage of book events such as panel discussions, book fairs, book signings, readings by authors and tours of bookstores around the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN 3 covers public affairs events, congressional hearings and history programming.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The weekday programming on C-SPAN3 (from the morning — anywhere from 6 to 8:30 a.m. — to 8 p.m.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Eastern Time) features uninterrupted live public affairs events, in particular political events from Washington, D.C.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Each weekend since January 8, 2011, the network has broadcast 48 hours of programming dedicated to the history of the United States, under the umbrella title *American History TV*.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The programming covers the history of the U.S. from the founding of the nation through the late 20th century.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Programs include *American Artifacts*, which is dedicated to exploring museums, archives and historical sites, and *Lectures in History*, featuring major university history professors giving lectures on U.S. history.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2009, C-SPAN3 aired an eight-installment series of interviews from the Robert J.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Dole Institute of Politics at the University of Kansas, which featured historian Richard Norton Smith and Vice President Walter Mondale, among other interviewees.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN has also occasionally produced special episodes and series.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 1989, C-SPAN celebrated its 10th anniversary with a three-hour retrospective on the history of the network.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 1994, *Booknotes* collaborated with Lincoln scholar Harold Holzer to produce reenactments of the 1858 Lincoln–Douglas debates for the network's 15th anniversary.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The Alexis de Tocqueville Tour: Exploring Democracy in America and *American Writers: A Journey Through History* took viewers on tours of the United States, themed around Alexis de Tocqueville's travels and the works of 40 famous American writers, respectively.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The year-long series *American Presidents: Life Portraits*, produced to commemorate the 20th anniversary of C-SPAN, won a Peabody Award.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The network has also produced special feature documentaries on the history of various American institutions and landmarks.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2005, C-SPAN hosted a 25-hour "call-in marathon" and essay contest, the winner of which was invited to co-host an hour of the broadcast, to commemorate 25 years of taking viewer telephone calls.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2015, C-SPAN premiered *Landmark Cases: Historic Supreme Court Decisions*, a 12-part mini-series about influential cases decided by the United States Supreme Court.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] A second season, also 12 episodes, aired in 2018.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In addition to the three television networks, C-SPAN also broadcasts via C-SPAN Radio, which is carried on their owned-and-operated station WCSP-FM (90.1 FM) in the Washington, D.C., area with all three cable network feeds airing via HD Radio subchannels, and nationwide on XM Satellite Radio.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Its programming is also livestreamed on the C-SPAN website and TuneIn and is available via apps for iPhone and Android devices.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN Radio has a selective policy regarding its broadcast content, rather than duplicating the television network programming, although it does offer some audio simulcasts of programs such as *Washington Journal*.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Unique programming on the radio station includes oral histories, and some committee meetings and press conferences not shown on television due to programming commitments.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The station also compiles the Sunday morning talk shows for a same-day rebroadcast without commercials, in rapid succession.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN archival video is available through the C-SPAN Video Library, maintained at the Purdue Research Park in West Lafayette, Indiana.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Unveiled in August 2007, the C-SPAN Video Library contains all of the network's programming since 1987, totaling more than 160,000 hours at its completion of digitization and public debut in March 2010.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Older C-SPAN programming continues to be added to the library, dating back to the beginning of the network in 1979, and some limited earlier footage from the National Archives, such as film clips of Richard Nixon's 1972 trip to China, is available as well.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Most of the recordings before 1987 (when the C-SPAN Archive was established) were not saved, except for approximately 10,000 hours of video which are slated to be made available online.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] As of November 2021, the C-SPAN Video Library held over 271,000 hours of programming, and they have been viewed over 253 million times.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Described by media commentators as a major educational service and a valuable resource for researchers of politics and history, the C-SPAN Video Library has also had a major role in media and opposition research in several U.S. political campaigns.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Prior to the initiation of the C-SPAN Video Library, websites such as Metavid and voterwatch.org hosted House and Senate video records, however C-SPAN contested Metavid's usage of C-SPAN copyrighted footage.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The result was Metavid's removal of portions of the archive produced with C-SPAN's cameras, while preserving its archive of government-produced content.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN also engaged in actions to stop parties from making unauthorized uses of its content online, including its video of House and Senate proceedings.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Most notably, in May 2006, C-SPAN requested the removal of Stephen Colbert's performance at the White House Correspondents' Association Dinner from YouTube.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] After concerns by some webloggers, C-SPAN gave permission for Google Video to host the full event.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The new policy did not affect the public's right to use the public domain video coverage of the floor proceedings of the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN brought back the Convention Hub for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The decision drew some criticism from public interest and government transparency advocates, citing the fact that C-SPAN was designed as a public service.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] As of December 2019, C-SPAN has begun advertising on its online videos, with advertisements that can be skipped after five seconds.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN programming is available to stream through the C-SPAN Now mobile application, which features breaking news and short videos, as well as through C-SPAN Select, a smart television application.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN is operated by the National Cable Satellite Corporation (NCSC), a nonprofit organization.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Early chairmen included Bob Rosencrans, John Saeman, Ed Allen and Gene Schneider.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] As a non-commercial public service, C-SPAN receives most of its funding from subscriber fees charged to cable and direct-broadcast satellite (DBS) operators.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] As of 2012, C-SPAN received 6¢ of each subscriber's cable bill for an annual budget of $60 million.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN began airing internet commercials early in 2021 and now sells C-SPAN merchandise.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In September 2025, C-SPAN announced that it had reached an agreement with Alphabet Inc. and The Walt Disney Company to have its channels carried on YouTube TV and Hulu at a fee equal to those C-SPAN received from cable and satellite television companies.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] As the network is an independent entity, neither the cable industry nor Congress controls the content of its programming.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] As of January 2013, the network has 282 or 337 employees.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN had for many years led by co-CEOs Rob Kennedy and Susan Swain.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Founder and former CEO Brian Lamb had served as the executive chairman of the board of directors.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] On May 14, 2024, the C-SPAN board of directors announced that longtime CNN executive Sam Feist would become the new CEO.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] This announcement followed a national search initiated after Swain and Kennedy announced they would be retiring.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Swain remained CEO until Feist officially began his duties in the summer of 2024.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The majority of C-SPAN's employees are based at C-SPAN's headquarters located on Capitol Hill in Washington, D.C.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2003 television studios were opened in New York City and Denver, Colorado.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] These studios use digital equipment that can be controlled from Washington.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN also maintains archives in West Lafayette, Indiana, at the Purdue Research Park under the direction of Robert X.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The C-SPAN networks are available in more than 100 million households as of 2010, not including access to the C-SPAN websites.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] As of 2020, more than 20,000 telephone callers participate annually in discussions on *Washington Journal*.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] There are no official viewing statistics for C-SPAN because the network, which has no commercials or underwriting advertisements, does not use the Nielsen ratings.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN's public service nature has been praised as an enduring contribution to national knowledge.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 1987, Andrew Rosenthal wrote for *The New York Times* about C-SPAN's influence in political elections, arguing that C-SPAN's "blanket coverage" had expanded television journalism "into areas once shielded from general view".
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The network has received positive media coverage for providing public access to proceedings such as the Goldman Sachs Senate hearings, and the U.S.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] 2010 Healthcare Summit, while its everyday programming has been credited with providing the media and the general public with an intimate knowledge of U.S. political proceedings and people.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In an article on the 25th anniversary of the network, *The Washington Post* noted that C-SPAN's programming has been copied by television networks worldwide and credits the network with providing information about foreign politics to American viewers.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] According to *The New York Times*, C-SPAN's mission to record official events in Washington, D.C., makes it "one of a kind", particularly in the creation of the C-SPAN Video Library, which received significant press coverage.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Despite its stated commitment to providing politically balanced programming, C-SPAN and its shows such as *Washington Journal*, *Booknotes*, *Q & A*, and *After Words* have been accused by some liberal organizations of having a conservative bias.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In 2005, the media criticism organization Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting (FAIR) released a study of C-SPAN's morning telephone call-in show *Washington Journal*.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] In their six-month sample of guests, they identified 32 as "right-of-center" and 19 as "left-of-center"; they also noted people of color are underrepresented at 15% of the guest list.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] A 2007 survey released by the think tank Center for Economic and Policy Research reported that C-SPAN covered conservative think tanks more than left-of-center think tanks.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN offers a number of public services related to the network's public affairs programming.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN Classroom, a free membership service for teachers, began in July 1987 and offers help using C-SPAN resources for classes or research.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The C-SPAN School Bus, introduced in November 1993, traveled around the U.S. educating the public about government and politics using C-SPAN resources, and served as a mobile television studio.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The bus also recorded video footage of the places that it visited.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The two original buses were retired in 2010, and the C-SPAN Digital Bus was inaugurated, introducing the public to C-SPAN's enhanced digital products.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN has also equipped six Local Content Vehicles (LCVs) to travel the country and record unique political and historical stories, with each vehicle containing production and web-based technologies to produce on-the-spot content.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] C-SPAN has published ten books based on its programming; these contain original material and text taken from interview transcripts.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The first C-SPAN book, *C-SPAN: America's Town Hall*, was published in 1988.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Due to the open phone lines on *Washington Journal*, C-SPAN has been noted to have a tradition of prank calls.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Calls have ranged from crude jokes about Howard Stern and Baba Booey to racist tirades against Martin Luther King Jr. and questions regarding the size of Mitt Romney's penis.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] One particularly well-known instance happened in 2015, when during a segment on the Iran nuclear deal framework, a man calling himself Jack Strickland called in claiming to be from Bel-Air, California, before quoting parts of the theme song of *The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air* TV show.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] Obscenities have also made it into broadcasts, such as in 2014 where a caller said "The Republicans hate that nigger Obama." before being kicked off the air.
[src:alfred-f-young/c-span] The network implemented a three-second broadcast delay in 2016 to combat these types of calls.
